> - **Course:** PCEOL308 - DATA STRUCTURES LAB
> - **Module:** Module Experiment 2
> - **Topic:** Implementation of Stack and Linear Queue Using Arrays

<!-- SECTION_1_START -->
# 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

## 1.1 Formal Definition of a Stack

A **Stack** is a linear, non-primitive data structure that follows the **LIFO (Last In, First Out)** discipline, where insertion and deletion of elements are permitted only at one end, formally termed the **TOP** of the stack.

Mathematically, a stack `S` is an ordered collection of homogeneous elements `S = (s1, s2, ..., sn)` governed by the two fundamental axioms:

$$\text{PUSH}(S, x): \quad S \leftarrow (s_1, s_2, \dots, s_n, x)$$

$$\text{POP}(S): \quad S \leftarrow (s_1, s_2, \dots, s_{n-1})$$

The base pointer is the only element that has been in the collection the longest, and access is strictly limited to the most recently inserted element.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** A stack implemented using a one-dimensional static array is termed an **Array-based Stack** (or *Static Stack*). The variable `top` tracks the index of the uppermost element, initialized to `-1` to denote an empty stack.

## 1.2 Formal Definition of a Linear Queue

A **Linear Queue** is a linear data structure that adheres to the **FIFO (First In, First Out)** principle. It is logically equivalent to a real-world waiting line, where elements are appended at the **REAR** end and removed from the **FRONT** end.

The operation axioms for a queue `Q` are:

$$\text{ENQUEUE}(Q, x): \quad Q \leftarrow (s_1, s_2, \dots, s_n, x)$$

$$\text{DEQUEUE}(Q): \quad Q \leftarrow (s_2, s_3, \dots, s_n)$$

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Array-based Queue Pitfall:** In a *linear* (non-circular) queue, the pointers `front` and `rear` only ever increment. Once `rear` reaches `MAX - 1`, no further insertions are permitted, even if free memory exists at lower indices. This anomaly is resolved in **Circular Queue** (covered in Experiment 3).

## 1.3 Conceptual Analogy / Real-World Intuition

| Data Structure | Real-World Analogy | Memory Trick |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Stack** | A pile of plates in a cafeteria — you can only add or remove the topmost plate. | "**L**ast **I**n, **F**irst **O**ut" — the last plate placed is the first one picked up. |
| **Linear Queue** | A queue at a cinema ticket counter — newcomers join at the tail, service happens at the head. | "**F**irst **I**n, **F**irst **O**ut" — first in line is served first. |

## 1.4 Key Pointer Conventions (KTU Board Standard)

- **Empty Stack Condition:** `top == -1`
- **Full Stack Condition:** `top == MAX - 1`
- **Empty Linear Queue Condition:** `front == -1` (or `front > rear`)
- **Full Linear Queue Condition:** `rear == MAX - 1`
<!-- SECTION_1_END -->

<!-- SECTION_2_START -->
# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 Operational Logic of an Array-Based Stack

A static stack uses a one-dimensional array of capacity `MAX`. A single integer pointer `top` maintains the index of the most recently pushed element. The operational sequence is governed by strict boundary invariants.

### 2.1.1 The `PUSH` Operation (Insertion)

The `PUSH` operation places a new element `x` onto the stack at index `top + 1`. It is a **2-step guarded write**.

- **Step 1: Boundary Check (Overflow Guard).** Before writing, the system must verify that the array is not saturated. If `top == MAX - 1`, the structure cannot accept more elements — this is **Stack Overflow**.
- **Step 2: Increment and Write.** The pointer is advanced (`top = top + 1`), and the value `x` is written into `stack[top]`.

### 2.1.2 The `POP` Operation (Deletion)

The `POP` operation removes and returns the topmost element of the stack. It is a **2-step guarded read**.

- **Step 1: Boundary Check (Underflow Guard).** If `top == -1`, the stack has no elements to remove — this is **Stack Underflow**.
- **Step 2: Read and Decrement.** The value `stack[top]` is read into a temporary variable, and the pointer is retracted (`top = top - 1`).

### 2.1.3 The `PEEK` Operation (Inspection)

`PEEK` (or `STACKTOP`) returns the value at `stack[top]` *without* mutating the pointer. It is used for non-destructive lookups, such as precedence checks in expression parsing.

## 2.2 Operational Logic of an Array-Based Linear Queue

A static linear queue requires **two pointers**: `front` (the index from which elements are dequeued) and `rear` (the index at which new elements are enqueued).

### 2.2.1 The `ENQUEUE` Operation (Insertion)

- **Step 1: Boundary Check.** If `rear == MAX - 1`, the queue is full.
- **Step 2: Increment and Write.** `rear = rear + 1`; then `queue[rear] = x`. Note: `front` remains unchanged.
- **Initial State Convention:** If the queue is empty, `front = 0` and `rear = -1`.

### 2.2.2 The `DEQUEUE` Operation (Deletion)

- **Step 1: Boundary Check.** If `front == -1` or `front > rear`, the queue is empty.
- **Step 2: Read and Advance.** The value `queue[front]` is returned, and `front = front + 1`.
- **Memory Reset (Optional but Recommended):** When the queue becomes empty after a `DEQUEUE`, KTU examiners often expect the pointers to be **reset to their initial state** (`front = -1; rear = -1;`) to allow reuse. Failure to do this is a common mark-deduction error.

## 2.3 KTU Formula & Cheat Sheet (Static Implementations)

| Operation | Stack (using array) | Linear Queue (using array) | Time Complexity | Auxiliary Space |
| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Insertion** | `top++; arr[top] = x;` | `rear++; arr[rear] = x;` | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ |
| **Deletion** | `x = arr[top]; top--;` | `x = arr[front]; front++;` | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ |
| **Overflow Condition** | `top == MAX - 1` | `rear == MAX - 1` | — | — |
| **Underflow Condition** | `top == -1` | `front == -1` $\mid$ `front > rear` | — | — |
| **Initial Pointer State** | `top = -1` | `front = -1; rear = -1` | — | — |
| **Peek / Front Access** | `arr[top]` | `arr[front]` | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ |
| **Display (Full Traversal)** | `for(i = top; i >= 0; i--)` | `for(i = front; i <= rear; i++)` | $\mathcal{O}(n)$ | $\mathcal{O}(1)$ |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why pointer manipulation matters in KTU practicals:** Most student errors in the DS Lab viva arise from forgetting the `top == -1` (or `front == -1`) underflow check. The university lab record demands that *every* deletion operation begins with this guard, and marks are specifically awarded for this boundary check (typically 2 marks out of 14).

## 2.4 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Stacks** form the backbone of compilers for parsing expressions, implementing recursion (function call stack), backtracking algorithms (e.g., Depth-First Search, maze solvers), and the **undo/redo** mechanism in modern IDEs and text editors.
- **Linear Queues** are deployed in CPU process scheduling (FIFO scheduling), printer spoolers, I/O buffers, and Breadth-First Search (BFS) traversal in graph algorithms.
<!-- SECTION_2_END -->

<!-- SECTION_3_START -->
# 3. Step-by-Step Implementations & Analytical Trace

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Lab Language Mandate:** The official 2024 Scheme B.Tech syllabus prescribes the **C programming language** for PCEOL308. Implementations in C are mandatory for the End Semester Evaluation. All code blocks below are ANSI-C compliant, compile cleanly under `gcc -std=c11`, and use `printf`/`scanf` exclusively for I/O.

## 3.1 Complete C Implementation — Stack Using Array

```c
/* Experiment 2(a): Array-based Stack Implementation
   Author: [Student Name], Roll No: [___], Batch: [___] */
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 100

int stack[MAX];
int top = -1;   /* Sentinel: -1 indicates EMPTY stack */

/* 1. PUSH Operation */
void push(int x) {
    /* Overflow Guard: required to prevent undefined memory writes */
    if (top == MAX - 1) {
        printf("\n[ERROR] STACK OVERFLOW: Cannot push %d\n", x);
        return;
    }
    top = top + 1;          /* Step 1: Advance the pointer */
    stack[top] = x;         /* Step 2: Write to the new top */
    printf("%d pushed onto the stack.\n", x);
}

/* 2. POP Operation */
int pop(void) {
    /* Underflow Guard */
    if (top == -1) {
        printf("\n[ERROR] STACK UNDERFLOW: Stack is empty.\n");
        return -9999;       /* Sentinel return for failure */
    }
    int temp = stack[top];  /* Step 1: Read the topmost element */
    top = top - 1;          /* Step 2: Retract the pointer */
    return temp;
}

/* 3. PEEK Operation */
int peek(void) {
    if (top == -1) {
        printf("\n[INFO] Stack is empty.\n");
        return -9999;
    }
    return stack[top];
}

/* 4. DISPLAY Operation (Top to Bottom Traversal) */
void display(void) {
    if (top == -1) {
        printf("\n[INFO] Stack is empty. Nothing to display.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("\n--- Current Stack (Top to Bottom) ---\n");
    for (int i = top; i >= 0; i--) {
        printf("|  %d  |\n", stack[i]);
        if (i != 0) printf("|------|\n");
    }
    printf("------- (BASE)\n");
}

int main(void) {
    int choice, value;
    while (1) {
        printf("\n========== STACK MENU ==========\n");
        printf("1. PUSH\n2. POP\n3. PEEK\n4. DISPLAY\n5. EXIT\n");
        printf("Enter your choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);

        switch (choice) {
            case 1:
                printf("Enter integer to push: ");
                scanf("%d", &value);
                push(value);
                break;
            case 2:
                value = pop();
                if (value != -9999) printf("Popped value: %d\n", value);
                break;
            case 3:
                value = peek();
                if (value != -9999) printf("Top element: %d\n", value);
                break;
            case 4:
                display();
                break;
            case 5:
                return 0;
            default:
                printf("Invalid choice. Try again.\n");
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.1.1 Analytical Trace — Stack Operations

Consider an initially empty stack with `MAX = 5`. We execute: `push(10), push(20), pop(), push(30), peek()`.

| Step | Operation | `top` Before | Action Executed | `top` After | Stack State (Top -> Base) |
| :---: | :--- | :---: | :--- | :---: | :--- |
| 1 | `push(10)` | -1 | `top++`; `stack[0]=10` | 0 | `[10]` |
| 2 | `push(20)` | 0 | `top++`; `stack[1]=20` | 1 | `[20, 10]` |
| 3 | `pop()` | 1 | `temp=20`; `top--` | 0 | `[10]` (returns 20) |
| 4 | `push(30)` | 0 | `top++`; `stack[1]=30` | 1 | `[30, 10]` |
| 5 | `peek()` | 1 | Returns `stack[1]` | 1 | `[30, 10]` (no mutation) |

## 3.2 Complete C Implementation — Linear Queue Using Array

```c
/* Experiment 2(b): Array-based Linear Queue Implementation */
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 100

int queue[MAX];
int front = -1;   /* Sentinel: -1 indicates EMPTY queue */
int rear  = -1;

/* 1. ENQUEUE Operation */
void enqueue(int x) {
    /* Overflow Guard */
    if (rear == MAX - 1) {
        printf("\n[ERROR] QUEUE OVERFLOW: Cannot enqueue %d\n", x);
        return;
    }
    if (front == -1) front = 0;  /* First insertion: anchor front */
    rear = rear + 1;
    queue[rear] = x;
    printf("%d enqueued into the queue.\n", x);
}

/* 2. DEQUEUE Operation */
int dequeue(void) {
    /* Underflow Guard */
    if (front == -1 || front > rear) {
        printf("\n[ERROR] QUEUE UNDERFLOW: Queue is empty.\n");
        return -9999;
    }
    int temp = queue[front];
    front = front + 1;

    /* Memory reset when queue becomes empty */
    if (front > rear) {
        front = -1;
        rear  = -1;
    }
    return temp;
}

/* 3. DISPLAY Operation (Front to Rear Traversal) */
void display(void) {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("\n[INFO] Queue is empty.\n");
        return;
    }
    printf("\n--- Current Queue (Front to Rear) ---\n");
    for (int i = front; i <= rear; i++) {
        printf("[%d] -> %d\n", i, queue[i]);
    }
    printf("--- END ---\n");
}

int main(void) {
    int choice, value;
    while (1) {
        printf("\n========== LINEAR QUEUE MENU ==========\n");
        printf("1. ENQUEUE\n2. DEQUEUE\n3. DISPLAY\n4. EXIT\n");
        printf("Enter your choice: ");
        scanf("%d", &choice);

        switch (choice) {
            case 1:
                printf("Enter integer to enqueue: ");
                scanf("%d", &value);
                enqueue(value);
                break;
            case 2:
                value = dequeue();
                if (value != -9999) printf("Dequeued value: %d\n", value);
                break;
            case 3:
                display();
                break;
            case 4:
                return 0;
            default:
                printf("Invalid choice.\n");
        }
    }
}
```

### 3.2.1 Analytical Trace — Linear Queue Operations

Consider `MAX = 5`, initial state `front = -1; rear = -1`. We execute: `enqueue(10), enqueue(20), enqueue(30), dequeue(), dequeue()`.

| Step | Operation | `front` Before | `rear` Before | Action Executed | `front` After | `rear` After | Queue State |
| :---: | :--- | :---: | :---: | :--- | :---: | :---: | :--- |
| 1 | `enqueue(10)` | -1 | -1 | `front=0`; `rear=0`; `q[0]=10` | 0 | 0 | `[10]` |
| 2 | `enqueue(20)` | 0 | 0 | `rear=1`; `q[1]=20` | 0 | 1 | `[10, 20]` |
| 3 | `enqueue(30)` | 0 | 1 | `rear=2`; `q[2]=30` | 0 | 2 | `[10, 20, 30]` |
| 4 | `dequeue()` | 0 | 2 | `temp=10`; `front=1` | 1 | 2 | `[_, 20, 30]` (returns 10) |
| 5 | `dequeue()` | 1 | 2 | `temp=20`; `front=2` | 2 | 2 | `[_, _, 30]` (returns 20) |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why Step 5 doesn't reset pointers:** In the code above, the reset (`front = -1; rear = -1`) only triggers when `front > rear`. Here, `front == rear == 2`, so the queue still logically contains the element `30`. After one more `dequeue()`, the condition `front > rear` will activate, and the pointers will be reset.

## 3.3 Mathematical Formulation of Memory Consumption

For a stack or queue of `n` elements stored in an array of capacity `MAX`:

$$\text{Wasted Cells} = MAX - n$$

$$\text{Utilization Ratio} = \dfrac{n}{MAX}$$

$$\text{Total Pointer Overhead} = \begin{cases} 1 \times \text{sizeof}(\text{int}) & \text{for Stack (only `top`)} \\ 2 \times \text{sizeof}(\text{int}) & \text{for Linear Queue (`front` and `rear`)} \end{cases}$$

> [!WARNING]
> **Examiners' Trap Question:** A linear queue with `MAX = 5` containing `[10, 20, 30]` (where `front = 2, rear = 4`) cannot accept a new element even though 2 cells are free. The wasted memory is precisely **2 cells = 40% utilization loss**. This is the **prime motivation** for the **Circular Queue** data structure (Module Experiment 3).
<!-- SECTION_3_END -->

<!-- SECTION_4_START -->
# 4. Structural Diagrams & Schematics

## 4.1 Block-Level Functional Architecture — Stack Module

The following Mermaid block diagram maps the runtime control flow of the stack module, illustrating the decision points (overflow/underflow guards) and the data path.

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Input: choice] --> B{choice == PUSH?}
    B -- Yes --> C{top == MAX-1?}
    C -- Yes --> D[Print OVERFLOW Error]
    C -- No --> E[top = top + 1]
    E --> F[stack top = x]
    F --> G[Print Success Message]
    B -- No --> H{choice == POP?}
    H -- Yes --> I{top == -1?}
    I -- Yes --> J[Print UNDERFLOW Error]
    I -- No --> K[temp = stack top]
    K --> L[top = top - 1]
    L --> M[Return temp]
    H -- No --> N{choice == PEEK?}
    N -- Yes --> O{top == -1?}
    O -- Yes --> P[Print Empty Message]
    O -- No --> Q[Return stack top]
    N -- No --> R{choice == DISPLAY?}
    R -- Yes --> S[Traverse top to 0]
    S --> T[Print all elements]
    R -- No --> U{choice == EXIT?}
    U -- Yes --> V[Terminate Program]
    U -- No --> W[Print Invalid Choice]
```

## 4.2 Stack Memory State — Visual Snapshot

```mermaid
graph LR
    base[BASE: index 0] --> idx1[index 1]
    idx1 --> idx2[index 2]
    idx2 --> idx3[index 3: TOP]
    idx3 --> empty1[index 4: EMPTY]
    empty1 --> empty2[index 5: EMPTY]
    empty2 --> empty3[index MAX-1: BOUND]
```

**State Description:** A partially filled stack with 4 elements (`top = 3`). Indices 4 through `MAX-1` are **unallocated logical cells** — writing to them triggers overflow.

## 4.3 Block-Level Functional Architecture — Linear Queue Module

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[User Input: choice] --> B{choice == ENQUEUE?}
    B -- Yes --> C{rear == MAX-1?}
    C -- Yes --> D[Print QUEUE OVERFLOW]
    C -- No --> E{front == -1?}
    E -- Yes --> F[front = 0]
    E -- No --> G[Skip Reset]
    F --> H[rear = rear + 1]
    G --> H
    H --> I[queue rear = x]
    I --> J[Print Success]
    B -- No --> K{choice == DEQUEUE?}
    K -- Yes --> L{front == -1 OR front > rear?}
    L -- Yes --> M[Print QUEUE UNDERFLOW]
    L -- No --> N[temp = queue front]
    N --> O[front = front + 1]
    O --> P{front > rear?}
    P -- Yes --> Q[Reset: front = -1, rear = -1]
    P -- No --> R[Skip Reset]
    Q --> S[Return temp]
    R --> S
    K -- No --> T{choice == DISPLAY?}
    T -- Yes --> U[Traverse front to rear]
    U --> V[Print all elements]
    T -- No --> W{choice == EXIT?}
    W -- Yes --> X[Terminate]
    W -- No --> Y[Invalid Choice]
```

## 4.4 Linear Queue Memory Drift — The Wastage Phenomenon

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[index 0: VOID] --> B[index 1: VOID]
    B --> C[index 2: FRONT = 20]
    C --> D[index 3: 30]
    D --> E[index 4: REAR = 40]
    E --> F[index 5: VOID]
    F --> G[index MAX-1: BOUND]
```

**Diagnostic:** Two dequeue operations have already removed elements at indices 0 and 1, leaving **logical holes** in the array. Although 2 cells are free, `rear == MAX - 1` blocks further insertions. This is the canonical **linear queue wastage problem** that motivates circular buffers.
<!-- SECTION_4_END -->

<!-- SECTION_5_START -->
# 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

> **[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024, Q1.A]**
>
> **Q1.** Differentiate between a **Stack** and a **Linear Queue** with respect to insertion, deletion, and underlying principle.
>
> **Model Answer:**
> | Property | Stack | Linear Queue |
> | :--- | :--- | :--- |
> | **Principle** | LIFO (Last In, First Out) | FIFO (First In, First Out) |
> | **Insertion End** | Top | Rear |
> | **Deletion End** | Top | Front |
> | **Pointer Count** | 1 (`top`) | 2 (`front`, `rear`) |
> | **Overflow Check** | `top == MAX - 1` | `rear == MAX - 1` |
> | **Example Use** | Function call stack, undo | Process scheduling, BFS |
> *(3 marks awarded for covering principle + both operation ends + one pointer difference.)*

> **[KTU University Exam — Model Paper 2024, Q1.B]**
>
> **Q2.** What is **Stack Overflow** and **Stack Underflow**? State the conditions under which each occurs in an array-based implementation with `MAX = 50`.
>
> **Model Answer:**
> - **Stack Overflow:** The condition when the stack is completely full and a `PUSH` operation is attempted. **Condition:** `top == MAX - 1` (i.e., `top == 49` for `MAX = 50`). The new element cannot be accommodated, and the program must reject the insertion to prevent memory corruption.
> - **Stack Underflow:** The condition when the stack is empty and a `POP` or `PEEK` operation is attempted. **Condition:** `top == -1`. The program must return an error sentinel rather than accessing invalid memory.

## 5.2 Part B — Long Answer Questions (14 Marks Each)

> **Internal Choice Mandate:** Per KTU 2024 ESE regulations, Part B questions carry 14 marks with sub-parts (a) and (b), each of 7 marks. Students must answer **either** Question A **or** Question B.

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam — Dec 2023, Modified]`

> **(a)** [7 Marks] Write a complete C program to implement a **Stack using an array** with the following operations: `PUSH`, `POP`, `PEEK`, and `DISPLAY`. Use a global array `int s[100]` and global variable `int top`.
>
> **(b)** [7 Marks] Trace the following sequence of operations on an initially empty stack with `MAX = 6`. Show the state of the stack and the value of `top` after each step:
> `push(5), push(12), pop(), push(7), push(20), pop(), push(3), peek()`

#### Model Solution for Q.A(a)

The complete implementation is provided in **Section 3.1** above. The evaluator checklist is:

| Component | Marks |
| :--- | :---: |
| Correct `#include` and `#define MAX 100` | 0.5 |
| Global declaration of `s[]` and `top = -1` | 0.5 |
| `PUSH` function with overflow guard | 1.5 |
| `POP` function with underflow guard and return value | 1.5 |
| `PEEK` function | 1.0 |
| `DISPLAY` function (top-down traversal) | 1.0 |
| `main` with menu-driven `switch` loop | 1.0 |

#### Model Solution for Q.A(b) — Stack Trace

| Step | Operation | `top` After | Stack State (Top -> Base) | Returned Value |
| :---: | :--- | :---: | :--- | :---: |
| 1 | `push(5)` | 0 | `[5]` | — |
| 2 | `push(12)` | 1 | `[12, 5]` | — |
| 3 | `pop()` | 0 | `[5]` | **12** |
| 4 | `push(7)` | 1 | `[7, 5]` | — |
| 5 | `push(20)` | 2 | `[20, 7, 5]` | — |
| 6 | `pop()` | 1 | `[7, 5]` | **20** |
| 7 | `push(3)` | 2 | `[3, 7, 5]` | — |
| 8 | `peek()` | 2 | `[3, 7, 5]` (no change) | **3** |

---

### **Question B (14 Marks)** `[KTU University Exam — June 2024, Modified]`

> **(a)** [7 Marks] Write a complete C program to implement a **Linear Queue using an array** with operations `ENQUEUE`, `DEQUEUE`, and `DISPLAY`. Reset `front` and `rear` to `-1` whenever the queue becomes empty.
>
> **(b)** [7 Marks] A linear queue of `MAX = 5` is currently in the state: `front = 2, rear = 4`, with elements `[20, 30, 40]` at indices 2, 3, 4 respectively. **(i)** What happens if you attempt `enqueue(50)`? **(ii)** Suggest the remedy and briefly explain how the same situation is resolved using a **circular queue**.

#### Model Solution for Q.B(a)

The complete implementation is provided in **Section 3.2** above. The evaluator checklist is:

| Component | Marks |
| :--- | :---: |
| Correct header and `#define MAX 100` | 0.5 |
| Global `queue[]`, `front = -1`, `rear = -1` | 0.5 |
| `ENQUEUE` with overflow check and `front` initialization | 2.0 |
| `DEQUEUE` with underflow check and return value | 1.5 |
| Pointer reset when `front > rear` | 1.0 |
| `DISPLAY` (front-to-rear traversal) | 0.5 |
| `main` with menu loop | 1.0 |

#### Model Solution for Q.B(b)

**(i) Attempting `enqueue(50)`:**
Since `rear == 4 == MAX - 1`, the overflow condition is triggered. The program prints **`QUEUE OVERFLOW: Cannot enqueue 50`** and rejects the insertion. Although cells at indices 0 and 1 are logically unused, the linear queue cannot reuse them.

**(ii) Remedy via Circular Queue:**
In a **Circular Queue**, `rear` is updated using modular arithmetic:

$$rear = (rear + 1) \mod MAX$$

Applying this to the current state `(front = 2, rear = 4, MAX = 5)`:

$$rear_{\text{new}} = (4 + 1) \mod 5 = 0$$

This wraps the `rear` pointer back to index 0, allowing `enqueue(50)` to succeed and filling the previously wasted cells. Thus, **100% memory utilization** is achieved — the central advantage of the circular buffer.

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Pitfalls — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Missing underflow check in `DEQUEUE`:** Many students forget to verify `front == -1` or `front > rear` before accessing `queue[front]`. This causes undefined behavior and loses **2 marks** per sub-question.
> 2. **Pointer reset omission in linear queue:** The KTU marking scheme specifically awards 1 mark for resetting `front` and `rear` to `-1` after the queue empties. Skipping this is a frequent mark-loss.
> 3. **Confusion between `top` and `rear`:** Stack and queue pointer semantics differ. Stack uses a *single* pointer moving up/down; queue uses *two* pointers that only *increment*. Misnaming variables costs 1–2 marks.
> 4. **Returning garbage value on underflow:** Functions must return a documented sentinel (e.g., `-9999`) and print an error. A bare `return;` from an `int` function is undefined behavior and loses **1 mark**.
> 5. **Forgetting to update `front` to 0 on first `enqueue`:** When the queue is empty (`front == -1`), the very first insertion must set `front = 0` before `rear` is incremented. Missing this produces an off-by-one error.

## 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- **Stack Principle:** LIFO. Single pointer `top` initialized to `-1`. Operations: `PUSH`, `POP`, `PEEK`, `DISPLAY`.
- **Queue Principle:** FIFO. Two pointers: `front = -1`, `rear = -1`. Operations: `ENQUEUE`, `DEQUEUE`, `DISPLAY`.
- **Boundary Conditions (memorize verbatim):**
  - Stack Overflow: `top == MAX - 1`
  - Stack Underflow: `top == -1`
  - Queue Overflow: `rear == MAX - 1`
  - Queue Underflow: `front == -1` **OR** `front > rear`
- **Time Complexity:** Every core operation on both structures is $\mathcal{O}(1)$. Only `DISPLAY` is $\mathcal{O}(n)$.
- **Space Complexity:** $\mathcal{O}(MAX)$ for the static array, regardless of the number of elements actually stored.
- **Linear Queue Limitation:** Once `rear` reaches `MAX - 1`, no further insertions are possible, even if memory exists at lower indices. This is the **memory wastage problem**.
- **Resolution:** Use a **Circular Queue** (Experiment 3) where `rear = (rear + 1) % MAX` and `front = (front + 1) % MAX`.
- **Mandatory First Insertion Logic in Queue:** Always set `front = 0` when `front == -1` before incrementing `rear`. This is a classic KTU board question.
- **Pointer Reset (Best Practice):** After `DEQUEUE` causes `front > rear`, reset both pointers to `-1` to allow fresh data entry. This demonstrates good memory hygiene in your viva.
- **Real-world mapping:** Stack = recursion, undo, DFS, browser back-button. Queue = CPU scheduling, BFS, printer spool, customer service lines.
- **Viva Favorites:** *"Why is `top` initialized to `-1` and not `0`?"* — Because `-1` is a clean sentinel that immediately signals an empty stack and yields correct arithmetic for the first insertion (`top + 1 = 0`).
