## SECTION 1: Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Priority Queue (PQ)

A **Priority Queue** is an abstract data type (ADT) in which each element is associated with a *priority value*, and deletions (or accesses) always return the element with the **highest priority** (or lowest, depending on convention), irrespective of the order in which elements were inserted. It generalises the FIFO (First-In-First-Out) policy of a normal queue.

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU 2024 Definition (Precise):** A Priority Queue is a container ADT that supports the insertion of arbitrary elements and the extraction of the maximum-priority (or minimum-priority) element in $O(\log n)$ time when implemented using a heap, or $O(n)$ time when implemented using a sorted/unsorted array.

**Conceptual Analogy (Real-World Intuition):**
Imagine the *Emergency Room* of a government hospital. Patients arrive in a long line (FIFO would be unfair here), but the doctor does NOT call them in arrival order. A patient with a heart attack (Priority = 1, highest) is treated before a patient with a mild fever (Priority = 5, lowest), even if the fever patient arrived earlier. The hospital's waiting list is, in essence, a **Priority Queue** — *order of service is determined by urgency, not arrival time*.

In Data Structures, priority is typically represented as an integer key where:
- **Lower numerical value = Higher priority** (Min-Heap convention, common in textbooks)
- **Higher numerical value = Higher priority** (Max-Heap convention)

---

### 1.2 Deque (Double-Ended Queue)

A **Deque** (pronounced "deck") is a linear data structure that generalises both the **Stack** (LIFO) and the **Queue** (FIFO). It allows insertion and deletion of elements from **both ends** — the *front* and the *rear*.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Highlight:** A Deque is the *only* linear ADT among the queue family that permits $O(1)$ insertion AND $O(1)$ deletion at both the front and rear ends, making it the most flexible queue variant in the syllabus.

**Conceptual Analogy (Real-World Intuition):**
Picture a *garage driveway* that is open on both sides. A car can enter from the *front gate* or the *back gate*, and a car can also exit from either gate. The driveway itself acts as a **Deque** — *additions and removals can happen at either end with equal ease*. Compare this to a normal queue at a cinema ticket counter, where entry is only from the rear and exit only from the front.

There are two common restricted variants of a Deque:

| Variant | Allowed Operations | Real-World Analogy |
|---|---|---|
| **Input-Restricted Deque** | Insertion only at rear; deletion at both ends | A toll booth where vehicles can exit from either lane but can only enter from one designated entry |
| **Output-Restricted Deque** | Insertion at both ends; deletion only at front | A one-way escalator that allows people to step on from either floor but can only step off at the bottom |

---

### 1.3 Circular Queue (Ring Buffer)

A **Circular Queue** is a linear data structure that overcomes the **"memory wastage"** limitation of a simple linear array-based queue. The last position is logically connected back to the first position, forming a circle. This is achieved using **modular arithmetic** on the `rear` and `front` indices.

> [!NOTE]
> **Core Definition:** A Circular Queue is a FIFO data structure in which the `rear` pointer, upon reaching the end of the underlying array, *wraps around* to index $0$ using the operation $\text{rear} = (\text{rear} + 1) \mod N$, where $N$ is the array capacity.

**Conceptual Analogy (Real-World Intuition):**
Think of a *circular dining table with 6 chairs* and a *rotating serving dish* mechanism. When the dish finishes serving chair #6, instead of stopping (as a linear queue would), it *wraps around* and starts serving from chair #1 again. The 6 chairs represent the fixed array, and the serving dish's position represents the `rear` pointer. This wrapping behaviour is the defining feature of a **Circular Queue** and is the reason it never wastes memory.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why Circular Queue Exists — The Linear Queue Problem:** In a simple array-based queue, after several `enqueue` and `dequeue` operations, the `rear` pointer reaches the end of the array, even though there may be *vacant slots* at the front. The queue is reported as **"FULL"** even though memory is unused. This phenomenon is called **"false overflow"** or **"logical full"** state, and the circular queue eliminates it completely.
