## SECTION 2: Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Priority Queue — Operational Breakdown

A priority queue implemented with an array can be done in two ways. The KTU 2024 lab module focuses on the **sorted-array insertion** approach because it offers $O(1)$ deletion of the highest-priority element.

**Why use a Sorted Array?**
- Insertion requires shifting elements: $O(n)$
- Deletion of max-priority is trivial — just remove from one end: $O(1)$
- Best for *applications with more deletions than insertions* (e.g., job schedulers)

**Operational Logic — Insert (sorted by ascending priority value):**
1. Check if queue is full: $\text{count} == N$
2. Find the correct position by linear scan (or binary search for $O(\log n)$ *search* but $O(n)$ *shift*)
3. Shift elements to the right to make room
4. Place the new element in the correct position
5. Increment $\text{count}$

**Operational Logic — Delete Highest Priority:**
1. Check if queue is empty: $\text{count} == 0$
2. The highest-priority element is always at index $0$ (in sorted-ascending order)
3. Shift all remaining elements to the left by one
4. Decrement $\text{count}$

---

### 2.2 Deque — Operational Breakdown

A Deque has **four fundamental operations**, all of which must be $O(1)$:

| Operation | Description | Direction |
|---|---|---|
| `insertFront(x)` | Add `x` at the front end | Front $\rightarrow$ Rear |
| `insertRear(x)` | Add `x` at the rear end | Front $\leftarrow$ Rear |
| `deleteFront()` | Remove and return element from front | Front $\rightarrow$ Rear |
| `deleteRear()` | Remove and return element from rear | Front $\leftarrow$ Rear |

**Operational Logic — Insert at Front:**
1. Check if deque is full: $\text{count} == N$
2. If first insertion, place at index $0$
3. Otherwise, decrement `front` (and wrap around if `front == 0` by setting `front = N - 1`)
4. Place element at new `front`
5. Increment $\text{count}$

**Operational Logic — Insert at Rear:**
1. Check if deque is full: $\text{count} == N$
2. If first insertion, place at index $0`
3. Otherwise, `rear = (rear + 1) mod N`
4. Place element at new `rear`
5. Increment $\text{count}$

---

### 2.3 Circular Queue — Operational Breakdown

The circular queue uses two pointers, `front` and `rear`, and the modulo operation is the heart of its implementation.

**Operational Logic — Enqueue (insert at rear):**
1. Check full condition: $(\text{rear} + 1) \mod N == \text{front}$
2. If first element, set `front = rear = 0`
3. Else: `rear = (rear + 1) mod N`
4. Place element at `arr[rear]`

**Operational Logic — Dequeue (delete from front):**
1. Check empty condition: $\text{front} == -1$
2. Store `arr[front]` as the return value
3. If only one element, reset to `front = rear = -1`
4. Else: `front = (front + 1) mod N`

---

### 2.4 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

> [!IMPORTANT]
> The following table summarises **all boundary conditions and key formulas** that the KTU 2024 examiner expects students to reproduce verbatim. Master this table — it is the single most important reference for the viva and written exams.

| Data Structure | Condition / Formula | LaTeX Form | Description |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Circular Queue** | Full State | $(\text{rear} + 1) \mod N == \text{front}$ | One slot is sacrificed as a sentinel to distinguish full from empty |
| **Circular Queue** | Empty State | $\text{front} == -1$ | Initial sentinel value before any insertion |
| **Circular Queue** | Number of Elements | $(\text{rear} - \text{front} + N) \mod N$ | Robust count that handles wrap-around |
| **Circular Queue** | Rear Update | $\text{rear} = (\text{rear} + 1) \mod N$ | Standard wrap-around for insertion |
| **Circular Queue** | Front Update | $\text{front} = (\text{front} + 1) \mod N$ | Standard wrap-around for deletion |
| **Circular Queue** | Capacity Used | $N - 1$ slots | Because one slot is always kept empty (sentinel) |
| **Priority Queue** | Full State | $\text{count} == N$ | When using a separate counter |
| **Priority Queue** | Empty State | $\text{count} == 0$ | When using a separate counter |
| **Priority Queue** | Delete Complexity | $O(1)$ (sorted array) | Remove from index $0$ |
| **Priority Queue** | Insert Complexity | $O(n)$ (sorted array) | Linear shift required |
| **Deque** | Full State | $\text{count} == N$ | All $N$ slots occupied |
| **Deque** | Empty State | $\text{count} == 0$ | No elements present |
| **Deque** | Front Wrap | $\text{front} = (N - 1)$ when $\text{front} == 0$ | Circular decrement |
| **General** | Amortised Insert/Delete | $O(1)$ | All three structures in the best case |

