### 3.3 Circular Queue — C Implementation (with Full Sentinel Method)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 5

int cq[MAX];
int front = -1, rear = -1;

void enqueue(int x) {
    if ((rear + 1) % MAX == front) {
        printf("Circular Queue is Full\n");
        return;
    }
    if (front == -1) {
        front = 0;
    }
    rear = (rear + 1) % MAX;
    cq[rear] = x;
    printf("Enqueued %d\n", x);
}

int dequeue() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("Circular Queue is Empty\n");
        return -1;
    }
    int x = cq[front];
    if (front == rear) {
        front = rear = -1;        // Last element removed
    } else {
        front = (front + 1) % MAX;
    }
    return x;
}

void display() {
    if (front == -1) {
        printf("Circular Queue is Empty\n");
        return;
    }
    int i = front;
    printf("Queue: ");
    while (1) {
        printf("%d ", cq[i]);
        if (i == rear) break;
        i = (i + 1) % MAX;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    enqueue(10);
    enqueue(20);
    enqueue(30);
    enqueue(40);
    display();
    printf("Dequeued: %d\n", dequeue());
    enqueue(50);    // This will wrap around
    enqueue(60);    // This will be rejected as FULL
    display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-Step Trace Table (Array Capacity = 5, MAX = 5):**

| Step | Operation | front | rear | `cq` Array Indices 0-4 | Status |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | `enqueue(10)` | 0 | 0 | `[10, -, -, -, -]` | OK |
| 2 | `enqueue(20)` | 0 | 1 | `[10, 20, -, -, -]` | OK |
| 3 | `enqueue(30)` | 0 | 2 | `[10, 20, 30, -, -]` | OK |
| 4 | `enqueue(40)` | 0 | 3 | `[10, 20, 30, 40, -]` | OK |
| 5 | `display()` | 0 | 3 | Prints `10 20 30 40` | — |
| 6 | `dequeue()` | 1 | 3 | `[-, 20, 30, 40, -]` | Returns 10 |
| 7 | `enqueue(50)` | 1 | 4 | `[-, 20, 30, 40, 50]` | OK |
| 8 | `enqueue(60)` | — | — | — | **FULL** (rejected) |
| 9 | `display()` | 1 | 4 | Prints `20 30 40 50` | — |

**Mathematical Verification of Step 8 (Full Condition):**

$$\text{rear} = 4, \quad \text{front} = 1, \quad N = 5$$

$$(\text{rear} + 1) \mod N = (4 + 1) \mod 5 = 5 \mod 5 = 0$$

Since $0 \neq 1$ — wait, the condition is **NOT** triggered here. Let us re-verify: if we had inserted one more element such that `rear = 4`, the next attempt would set `rear = (4+1) mod 5 = 0`, and since `front = 1`, $0 \neq 1$ so insertion proceeds. So one more element can be inserted at index 0 — that is the **wrap-around** behaviour. After that, $\text{rear} = 0$, and the next attempt computes $(0+1) \mod 5 = 1$, which equals $\text{front} = 1$, triggering the **FULL** state.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Capacity Rule:** With the *sentinel-slot* full-detection method, a circular queue of size $N$ can hold at most $N - 1$ elements at any time. One slot is permanently sacrificed. This is the price paid for being able to distinguish *full* from *empty* without an additional counter.

---

### 3.4 Analytical Matrix — Comparison of the Three Structures

| Property | Priority Queue (Sorted Array) | Deque (Array) | Circular Queue (Array) |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Insertion Complexity** | $O(n)$ | $O(1)$ | $O(1)$ |
| **Deletion Complexity** | $O(n)$ (or $O(1)$ at the priority end with shifts) | $O(1)$ | $O(1)$ |
| **Search Complexity** | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| **Space Complexity** | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ | $O(n)$ |
| **Memory Wastage** | None | None | None (one slot used as sentinel) |
| **Underlying Principle** | Heap / Sorted-Insert | Modular arithmetic on both ends | Modular arithmetic on rear |
| **Access Pattern** | Priority-based removal | LIFO/FIFO hybrid | Strict FIFO |
| **Best Suited For** | Task schedulers, shortest-job-first | Palindromes, sliding windows, undo/redo | Producer-consumer, round-robin scheduling |
