**(a) Explanation (7 marks):**

A **Circular Queue** is a FIFO data structure in which the `rear` pointer wraps around to index $0$ after reaching the end of the array, using the modulo operation. *(1 mark)*

**The False Overflow Problem:** In a simple linear array-based queue, after some `enqueue` and `dequeue` operations, the `rear` pointer reaches the last index even though there may be vacant slots at the front of the array. *(2 marks)*

**Example:** If an array of size 5 has `front = 3` and `rear = 4` (2 elements), we cannot insert a new element because `rear == 4 == MAX - 1`, even though indices 0, 1, 2 are empty. This is *false overflow* — the queue is logically NOT full, but the linear implementation rejects insertion. *(1 mark)*

**Solution via Circular Queue:** By using the modulo operation $\text{rear} = (\text{rear} + 1) \mod N$, the `rear` pointer wraps from index $N - 1$ back to index $0$, reusing the freed-up slots. *(2 marks)*

**Diagram:** *(Refer to Section 4.5 for the visual schematic; the KTU examiner awards 1 mark for a neat diagram showing front, rear, and the wrap-around arrow.)* *(1 mark)*

