### Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember (Rapid Revision Checklist)

- [ ] A **Priority Queue** serves elements based on *priority*, not arrival time. In a sorted-array implementation, insertion is $O(n)$ and deletion is $O(1)$ from the front.
- [ ] **Lower numerical priority value = Higher priority** (this is the most common convention; verify it in every exam question).
- [ ] A **Deque** supports $O(1)$ insertion AND $O(1)$ deletion at *both* ends. It is the most flexible linear queue variant.
- [ ] **Input-restricted deque** = insert only at rear; **Output-restricted deque** = delete only at front.
- [ ] A **Circular Queue** eliminates the *false overflow* problem of linear queues by using $\text{rear} = (\text{rear} + 1) \mod N$.
- [ ] The **full condition** for a circular queue is $(\text{rear} + 1) \mod N == \text{front}$, **NOT** $\text{rear} == N - 1$.
- [ ] The **empty condition** for a circular queue is $\text{front} == -1$.
- [ ] After deleting the *last element* in a circular queue, **always reset** $\text{front} = \text{rear} = -1$.
- [ ] Maximum number of elements a circular queue of size $N$ can hold is $N - 1$ (one slot is a sentinel).
- [ ] All three structures are implemented using **static arrays** in this lab module; no dynamic memory (`malloc`) is involved.
- [ ] **Time complexities to memorise:** Priority Queue insert = $O(n)$, delete = $O(1)$ from the priority end. Deque all ops = $O(1)$. Circular Queue enqueue/dequeue = $O(1)$.
- [ ] **Real-world engineering apps:** Priority Queue → CPU scheduling, Dijkstra's algorithm. Deque → Sliding window, undo-redo, palindrome checker. Circular Queue → Round-robin scheduling, producer-consumer, I/O buffering.
