## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Linked List (KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition)**
> A **Linked List** is a linear, dynamic data structure consisting of a sequence of **nodes**, where each node stores two things: (1) the **data** (payload) and (2) a **pointer/link** to the next node in the sequence. Unlike arrays, linked list elements are not stored in contiguous memory locations; instead, they are scattered in the heap and connected using pointers.

### 1.2 Node Structure (The Fundamental Building Block)

Each node is a self-referential structure (a structure containing a pointer to its own type):

```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};
```

- **data**: Holds the actual information (integer, float, character, or any user-defined type).
- **next**: A pointer that stores the memory address of the next node. If no node follows, it holds **NULL**.

### 1.3 Intuitive Real-World Analogy — The Treasure Hunt Train

Imagine a **train** where each compartment (boggie) has:
- **Passengers** → the *data*
- **A connecting hook** at the back → the *pointer to the next node*

The engine knows where the first compartment is (`head` pointer). Each compartment knows only about the one immediately behind it, but **not** about compartments ahead. If you want to reach the 10th compartment, you must walk through compartments 1 → 2 → 3 → ... → 10. This sequential traversal is exactly how a linked list works.

### 1.4 Types of Linked Lists Covered in KTU Lab Module 2

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Module 2 Focus Areas:**
> 1. **Singly Linked List (SLL)** — Each node points only to the next node.
> 2. **Doubly Linked List (DLL)** — Each node points to both the next and previous nodes.
> 3. **Circular Linked List (CLL)** — The last node's `next` points back to the head, forming a circle.

### 1.5 Why Linked Lists? (Advantages over Arrays)

| Feature | Array | Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| **Memory Allocation** | Static/Contiguous | Dynamic/Scattered |
| **Size** | Fixed at compile time | Grows/shrinks at runtime |
| **Insertion at Beginning** | O(n) — shift all elements | O(1) — just update head |
| **Random Access** | O(1) — via index | O(n) — must traverse |
| **Memory Wastage** | Possible (allocated but unused) | None — allocates as needed |
| **Cache Friendliness** | High (locality of reference) | Low (scattered nodes) |
