**Model Solution:**

**(a) Insert at End + Display:**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};
int main() {
    struct Node *head = NULL, *temp, *newNode;
    int n, value;
    printf("Enter number of nodes: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("Enter value: ");
        scanf("%d", &value);
        newNode = (struct Node *)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
        newNode->data = value;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;        // First node
        } else {
            temp = head;
            while (temp->next != NULL) temp = temp->next;  // Reach last
            temp->next = newNode;  // Append
        }
    }
    printf("Final List: ");
    temp = head;
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d -> ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("NULL\n");
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-Step Logic (7 marks breakdown):**
- *Step 1* (1 mark): Define node structure with `data` and `next`.
- *Step 2* (2 marks): Loop `n` times to read values and allocate new nodes using `malloc`.
- *Step 3* (2 marks): If list is empty, `head = newNode`; otherwise traverse to last and attach.
- *Step 4* (2 marks): Traverse from `head` and print each node's data until `NULL`.

