> [!WARNING]
> **🚨 KTU Examiner's Pitfall Callout — Where Students Lose Marks:**
> 1. **Forgetting to update `head` after reversal** — If you don't assign `*head = prev` at the end, the list appears empty even though the reversed chain exists. **Loses 2 marks.**
> 2. **Memory leak on deletion** — Always call `free()` on the deleted node, otherwise the examiner deducts 1 mark for "improper memory management."
> 3. **Confusing `temp->next->next` with `temp->next`** — When deleting the last node, many students traverse to the last node itself instead of the *second-last* node. This causes a NULL pointer dereference crash.
> 4. **Not handling empty list** — Always check `if (head == NULL)` as the **first** statement in every operation. Examiners check this edge case explicitly.
> 5. **Using `=` instead of `==`** in conditions like `if (temp == NULL)` — A common typo that the compiler may not always catch but the examiner will.

