## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Stack — Formal Definition

> [!NOTE]
> **Stack (KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition):** A *Stack* is a linear, dynamic data structure that follows the **LIFO (Last-In, First-Out)** discipline, where insertion and deletion of elements are restricted to occur at only one end, called the **TOP** of the stack.

When a stack is implemented using a **singly linked list**, there is no predefined upper bound on the number of elements (limited only by available heap memory). Each node dynamically holds two fields:
- a **DATA** field (the actual value), and
- a **NEXT pointer** field (address of the node below it).

Only a single external pointer, called `top`, is maintained. It always points to the most recently pushed node.

### 1.2 Queue — Formal Definition

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Queue (KTU 2024 Syllabus Definition):** A *Queue* is a linear, dynamic data structure that obeys the **FIFO (First-In, First-Out)** discipline. Insertion (enqueue) takes place at the **REAR** end, while deletion (dequeue) takes place at the **FRONT** end.

When a queue is implemented using a **singly linked list**, two external pointers are maintained: `front` (for deletion) and `rear` (for insertion). Both operations then take **O(1)** time.

### 1.3 Conceptual Analogies (Intuition for First-Time Learners)

| Concept | Real-World Analogy | Key Behaviour |
|---|---|---|
| **Stack** | A pile of plates in a cafeteria | You add/remove only the **top** plate |
| **Queue** | People standing in a ticket counter line | The person at the **front** is served first; new arrivals join at the **rear** |

> [!TIP]
> **Memory Trick:** **LIFO = Stack** (think "Last plate you kept is the First one you take"). **FIFO = Queue** (think "First person in line is the First one served").

### 1.4 Why Linked List Implementation?

Standard KTU Board Reason: The **array-based** stack/queue suffers from two limitations:
1. **Fixed size** — must be declared at compile time.
2. **Wastage** or **overflow** — even unused slots cannot be reclaimed.

A linked-list based implementation **eliminates both problems** because nodes are allocated and freed at runtime via `malloc()` and `free()`.

