## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Node Structure (Common for Both)

```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};
```

### 2.2 Stack Using Linked List — Operational Logic

**1. PUSH (Insert at TOP)**
- Allocate a new node.
- Store the data in `newNode->data`.
- Point `newNode->next` to current `top`.
- Update `top = newNode`.

**2. POP (Delete from TOP)**
- Check **Underflow** condition: if `top == NULL`, abort.
- Store `top` in a temporary pointer `temp`.
- Move `top = top->next`.
- Free `temp` and return its `data`.

**3. PEEK / DISPLAY** — Traverse from `top` to the last node.

### 2.3 Queue Using Linked List — Operational Logic

**1. ENQUEUE (Insert at REAR)**
- Allocate new node, fill data, set `next = NULL`.
- If `rear == NULL` (empty queue), set `front = rear = newNode`.
- Else, `rear->next = newNode; rear = newNode;`.

**2. DEQUEUE (Delete from FRONT)**
- Check **Underflow** condition: if `front == NULL`, abort.
- Store `front` in `temp`, move `front = front->next`.
- If `front` becomes `NULL` (single element case), set `rear = NULL`.
- Free `temp`, return its data.

### 2.4 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

| Operation | Stack (Linked List) | Queue (Linked List) | Boundary Condition |
|---|---|---|---|
| Insert (Push / Enqueue) | Modify `top` | Modify `rear` | Overflow: **not possible** in LL (only when `malloc` fails) |
| Delete (Pop / Dequeue) | Modify `top` | Modify `front` | Underflow: **`top == NULL`** / **`front == NULL`** |
| Peek / Front | `top->data` | `front->data` | Same underflow check |
| Time Complexity (Best / Avg / Worst) | **O(1) / O(1) / O(1)** | **O(1) / O(1) / O(1)** | All pointer ops are constant time |
| Space Complexity | **O(n)** | **O(n)** | n = number of elements |
| Auxiliary Traversal (Display) | **O(n)** | **O(n)** | Must walk the full chain |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU Board Favourite Comparison Line:** *Array implementation of stack costs O(n) for push in worst case (resizing); linked list guarantees O(1) always, at the cost of one extra pointer per node.*

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Stack** powers the *call stack* of every C program (function calls, recursion), the *undo-redo engine* in editors, and *DFS traversal*.
- **Queue** powers the *CPU ready queue* in operating systems, *BFS traversal* in graph algorithms, and *print/job scheduling* pipelines.
