## 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

### 3.1 Mathematical Derivation of Time Complexity

For the **Push** operation in stack using linked list, the total cost is:

$$
T_{push} = T_{malloc} + T_{assign} + T_{link} + T_{update}
$$

Step-by-step evaluation:

$$
\begin{aligned}
T_{malloc} &\approx c_1 \quad \text{(constant heap allocation time)} \\
T_{assign} &\approx c_2 \quad \text{(one statement: newNode->data = x)} \\
T_{link}   &\approx c_3 \quad \text{(one statement: newNode->next = top)} \\
T_{update} &\approx c_4 \quad \text{(one statement: top = newNode)} \\
\end{aligned}
$$

Therefore the asymptotic time complexity is:

$$
T_{push}(n) = c_1 + c_2 + c_3 + c_4 = \Theta(1)
$$

This proves the operation is independent of `n`, the number of existing elements. The same derivation applies to **Pop**, **Enqueue**, and **Dequeue**, because each performs only a **constant number of pointer manipulations**.

For **Display**, every node is visited exactly once, giving:

$$
T_{display}(n) = n \cdot c_5 = \Theta(n)
$$

### 3.2 Exhaustive Source Code (C) — KTU Lab Standard

#### 3.2.1 Stack Using Singly Linked List

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};

struct Node *top = NULL;

/* PUSH Operation */
void push(int x) {
    struct Node *newNode = (struct Node *)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed (Overflow)\n");
        return;
    }
    newNode->data = x;
    newNode->next = top;   // Step 1: link new node to current top
    top = newNode;         // Step 2: update top pointer
    printf("%d pushed onto stack\n", x);
}

/* POP Operation */
int pop() {
    if (top == NULL) {                 // Underflow check
        printf("Stack Underflow\n");
        return -1;
    }
    struct Node *temp = top;
    int popped = temp->data;
    top = top->next;                   // Step 1: move top
    free(temp);                        // Step 2: free old node
    return popped;
}

/* PEEK Operation */
int peek() {
    if (top == NULL) {
        printf("Stack is empty\n");
        return -1;
    }
    return top->data;
}

/* DISPLAY Operation */
void display() {
    if (top == NULL) {
        printf("Stack is empty\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node *temp = top;
    printf("Stack (top -> bottom): ");
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    push(10);
    push(20);
    push(30);
    display();
    printf("Popped: %d\n", pop());
    printf("Top element: %d\n", peek());
    display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-step trace after `push(10); push(20); push(30);`**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{After push(10)} &: top \to [10 \mid NULL] \\
\text{After push(20)} &: top \to [20 \mid *] \to [10 \mid NULL] \\
\text{After push(30)} &: top \to [30 \mid *] \to [20 \mid *] \to [10 \mid NULL] \\
\end{aligned}
$$

#### 3.2.2 Queue Using Singly Linked List

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};

struct Node *front = NULL;
struct Node *rear  = NULL;

/* ENQUEUE Operation */
void enqueue(int x) {
    struct Node *newNode = (struct Node *)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    if (newNode == NULL) {
        printf("Memory allocation failed (Overflow)\n");
        return;
    }
    newNode->data = x;
    newNode->next = NULL;
    if (rear == NULL) {                // Empty queue case
        front = rear = newNode;
    } else {
        rear->next = newNode;          // Link old rear to new node
        rear = newNode;                // Update rear
    }
    printf("%d enqueued\n", x);
}

/* DEQUEUE Operation */
int dequeue() {
    if (front == NULL) {               // Underflow check
        printf("Queue Underflow\n");
        return -1;
    }
    struct Node *temp = front;
    int val = temp->data;
    front = front->next;               // Step 1: move front
    if (front == NULL) {               // Single element case
        rear = NULL;
    }
    free(temp);                        // Step 2: free old node
    return val;
}

/* PEEK / FRONT Operation */
int peekFront() {
    if (front == NULL) {
        printf("Queue is empty\n");
        return -1;
    }
    return front->data;
}

/* DISPLAY Operation */
void display() {
    if (front == NULL) {
        printf("Queue is empty\n");
        return;
    }
    struct Node *temp = front;
    printf("Queue (front -> rear): ");
    while (temp != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", temp->data);
        temp = temp->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    enqueue(100);
    enqueue(200);
    enqueue(300);
    display();
    printf("Dequeued: %d\n", dequeue());
    printf("Front element: %d\n", peekFront());
    display();
    return 0;
}
```

**Step-by-step trace after `enqueue(100); enqueue(200); enqueue(300);`**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{After enqueue(100)} &: front \to [100 \mid NULL] \leftarrow rear \\
\text{After enqueue(200)} &: front \to [100 \mid *] \to [200 \mid NULL] \leftarrow rear \\
\text{After enqueue(300)} &: front \to [100 \mid *] \to [200 \mid *] \to [300 \mid NULL] \leftarrow rear \\
\end{aligned}
$$

### 3.3 Analytical Matrix — Comparison Snapshot

| Parameter | Stack (LL) | Queue (LL) |
|---|---|---|
| Discipline | LIFO | FIFO |
| Insertion end | Top (front of list) | Rear (end of list) |
| Deletion end | Top (front of list) | Front (front of list) |
| Number of pointers maintained | **1 (`top`)** | **2 (`front`, `rear`)** |
| Empty condition | `top == NULL` | `front == NULL` (and `rear == NULL`) |
| Typical exam trap | Forgetting `top = top->next` before `free` | Forgetting to set `rear = NULL` when last element is dequeued |

