#### Question B (14 Marks) `[KTU University Exam — June 2024]`

**(a) [7 Marks]** Write a C program to implement a **queue using a singly linked list** supporting `enqueue`, `dequeue`, `peekFront`, and `display` operations.

**(b) [7 Marks]** Explain why two pointers (`front` and `rear`) are required in a linked list queue but only one pointer (`top`) is sufficient for a linked list stack.

**Model Solution:**

**(a) Full C program** — (Refer to the implementation given in **Section 3.2.2** of these notes. Examiner expects `struct Node`, four operations, and menu-driven `main`.)

**(b) Explanation:**

- A **stack** inserts and deletes at the **same end** (TOP). Therefore, the single `top` pointer is sufficient to perform both `push` and `pop` in **O(1)**.
- A **queue** inserts at one end (REAR) and deletes at the opposite end (FRONT). If we maintain **only one pointer** at the front, we would have to walk through the entire list every time we want to enqueue — making insertion **O(n)**.
- Hence, we maintain two pointers: `front` (for `dequeue`) and `rear` (for `enqueue`). With both pointers available, every operation reduces to a **constant-time pointer update**.
- **Bonus point:** In the single-element case, both `front` and `rear` must be reset to `NULL` together; otherwise dangling references occur.

