# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 The Three Fundamental Operations

The complete experiment revolves around three logical operations, each implemented as a separate C function:

### Operation 1: Polynomial Creation (Insertion)
A new node is dynamically created using `malloc()` and appended to the end of the existing list to **maintain descending order of exponents**. The number of terms is decided by the user at runtime.

### Operation 2: Polynomial Display (Traversal)
The list is traversed from the head node to the last node (where `next == NULL`), and each term is printed in the standard mathematical format $a x^b$.

### Operation 3: Polynomial Addition (Merge of Two Sorted Lists)
This is the **core algorithmic operation** of the experiment. The logic is:

| Case | Condition | Action |
|:-----|:----------|:-------|
| **Equal exponents** | `p1->expo == p2->expo` | Add coefficients: `sum = p1->coeff + p2->coeff`. If `sum ≠ 0`, insert into result. |
| **Exponent of P1 is greater** | `p1->expo > p2->expo` | Copy the P1 term directly into the result. Advance `p1` only. |
| **Exponent of P2 is greater** | `p1->expo < p2->expo` | Copy the P2 term directly into the result. Advance `p2` only. |
| **End of one list** | `p1 == NULL` OR `p2 == NULL` | Copy all remaining nodes of the other list into the result. |

## 2.2 The Master Algorithm (KTU Board-Standard Pseudocode)

```
FUNCTION addPolynomials(p1_head, p2_head) -> result_head
    SET p1 = p1_head
    SET p2 = p2_head
    SET result_head = NULL
    SET result_tail = NULL

    WHILE p1 != NULL AND p2 != NULL
        IF p1->expo == p2->expo THEN
            sum_coeff = p1->coeff + p2->coeff
            IF sum_coeff != 0 THEN
                create new node with (sum_coeff, p1->expo)
                append to result list
            END IF
            ADVANCE p1, ADVANCE p2
        ELSE IF p1->expo > p2->expo THEN
            create new node with (p1->coeff, p1->expo)
            append to result list
            ADVANCE p1
        ELSE
            create new node with (p2->coeff, p2->expo)
            append to result list
            ADVANCE p2
        END IF
    END WHILE

    WHILE p1 != NULL
        copy p1 term to result
        ADVANCE p1
    END WHILE

    WHILE p2 != NULL
        copy p2 term to result
        ADVANCE p2
    END WHILE

    RETURN result_head
END FUNCTION
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why this works:** Because both input polynomials are sorted in **descending order of exponents**, this single-pass merge is correct. This is mathematically identical to the **merge step of the Merge Sort algorithm** — a fact KTU examiners love to test in viva voce.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Concept | Formula / Rule | Significance |
|:--------|:---------------|:-------------|
| General polynomial | $P(x) = \sum_{i=0}^{n} a_i x^i$ | Mathematical foundation |
| Storage in node | Node $= (\text{coeff}_i, \text{expo}_i, \text{next})$ | Data structure mapping |
| Like-term combination | $a x^n + b x^n = (a+b) x^n$ | Core addition rule |
| Unlike-term copy | $a x^m$ (unique) is copied as-is | Preserves sparse terms |
| Space complexity | $O(m + n)$ nodes for result | $m, n$ = terms in $P_1, P_2$ |
| Time complexity | $O(m + n)$ | Single linear traversal |
| Memory per node | **3 components** × `sizeof(int/pointer)` | Typically **12 or 16 bytes** on 32/64-bit systems |
| Ordering invariant | $\text{expo}_1 > \text{expo}_2 > \cdots > \text{expo}_k$ | Required for correct merge |
| Zero-coefficient rule | Skip node if `sum_coeff == 0` | Prevents $0x^n$ in output |

> [!NOTE]
> **Engineering Utility:** Polynomial addition via linked lists is foundational in **symbolic computation systems** (e.g., Mathematica, MATLAB's polynomial toolbox), **digital signal processing** (filter design using $z$-transforms), and **computer graphics** (Bézier curve evaluation). The sparse representation is crucial when most coefficients are zero.

## 2.4 Why Linked List and Not Array?

| Criterion | Array Representation | Linked List Representation |
|:----------|:---------------------|:---------------------------|
| **Memory** | Pre-allocates $n+1$ slots (wasteful for sparse) | Allocates exactly the number of non-zero terms |
| **Degree change** | Fixed at compile time | Dynamic, grows with input |
| **Insertion** | Shifting required ($O(n)$) | Constant-time append ($O(1)$ with tail pointer) |
| **Suitability for sparse** | Poor — wastes memory | Excellent — stores only non-zero terms |
| **Random access** | $O(1)$ (by index) | $O(n)$ (sequential) |
| **Preferred for** | Dense polynomials of known degree | Sparse, dynamically-sized polynomials |

The trade-off is clear: **linked lists win for the polynomial addition use case** because the data is naturally sparse and dynamically evolving.
