# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Exhaustive Worked Example (Board-Standard)

Let us trace the algorithm with concrete input. Consider:

$$P_1(x) = 8x^4 + 4x^3 + 2x^1 + 9$$

$$P_2(x) = 7x^4 + 5x^3 + 3x^2 + 6x^1 + 1$$

The linked list representations are:

| List | Node 1 | Node 2 | Node 3 | Node 4 | Node 5 |
|:-----|:-------|:-------|:-------|:-------|:-------|
| $P_1$ | `(8, 4)` | `(4, 3)` | `(2, 1)` | `(9, 0)` | — |
| $P_2$ | `(7, 4)` | `(5, 3)` | `(3, 2)` | `(6, 1)` | `(1, 0)` |

### Step-by-Step Trace Table

| Step | $p_1$ points to | $p_2$ points to | Comparison | Action | Result list (so far) |
|:----:|:----------------|:----------------|:-----------|:-------|:--------------------|
| 1 | `(8, 4)` | `(7, 4)` | $4 = 4$ | $8 + 7 = 15 \neq 0$ → insert `(15, 4)` | `(15, 4)` |
| 2 | `(4, 3)` | `(5, 3)` | $3 = 3$ | $4 + 5 = 9 \neq 0$ → insert `(9, 3)` | `(15, 4) → (9, 3)` |
| 3 | `(2, 1)` | `(3, 2)` | $1 < 2$ | Copy $P_2$ term → insert `(3, 2)` | `(15, 4) → (9, 3) → (3, 2)` |
| 4 | `(2, 1)` | `(6, 1)` | $1 = 1$ | $2 + 6 = 8 \neq 0$ → insert `(8, 1)` | `(15, 4) → (9, 3) → (3, 2) → (8, 1)` |
| 5 | `(9, 0)` | `(1, 0)` | $0 = 0$ | $9 + 1 = 10 \neq 0$ → insert `(10, 0)` | `(15, 4) → (9, 3) → (3, 2) → (8, 1) → (10, 0)` |
| 6 | `NULL` | `NULL` | Loop ends | All nodes consumed | Final result |

### Final Result

$$P_1(x) + P_2(x) = 15x^4 + 9x^3 + 3x^2 + 8x^1 + 10$$

The math can be verified directly:

$$(8+7)x^4 + (4+5)x^3 + 3x^2 + (2+6)x^1 + (9+1) = 15x^4 + 9x^3 + 3x^2 + 8x + 10 \checkmark$$

## 3.2 Edge-Case Derivations (Critical for Full Marks)

The KTU 2024 lab rubric specifically tests these edge cases. Each one is a 2-mark sub-question in the typical evaluation.

### Edge Case A: Zero Sum on Like Terms

Suppose we have $P_1 = 5x^2 + 3x$ and $P_2 = -5x^2 + 4x + 1$. When the algorithm reaches the $x^2$ terms:

$$\text{sum\_coeff} = 5 + (-5) = 0$$

**Correct action:** Skip insertion. The result must **not** contain a $0x^2$ term. This is why the inner `if (sum != 0)` check is mandatory.

$$P_1 + P_2 = 7x + 1$$

### Edge Case B: One Polynomial is Empty (Zero Polynomial)

If $P_1 = 0$ (i.e., `p1_head = NULL`), the result must be an **exact deep copy** of $P_2$.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Common Mistake:** Students often return `p2_head` directly instead of copying nodes. While this works functionally, it is **bad practice** in the lab evaluation because modifying the result would corrupt $P_2$. Always create new nodes for the result list.

### Edge Case C: Polynomials of Very Different Degrees

If $P_1 = x^{100}$ (1 term) and $P_2 = 1$ (1 term), the algorithm processes the unequal-exponent cases correctly: $100 > 0$ copies $P_1$'s term, then the inner loop exits when $p_1 = NULL$, and the outer loop copies the remaining term of $P_2$.

$$P_1 + P_2 = x^{100} + 1$$

### Edge Case D: Identical Polynomials (Doubling Effect)

If $P_1 = P_2 = 3x^2 + 2x + 1$, every exponent matches, and all coefficients double.

$$P_1 + P_2 = 6x^2 + 4x + 2$$

## 3.3 Complete C Implementation (KTU Reference Code)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Node {
    int coeff;
    int expo;
    struct Node *next;
};

typedef struct Node Node;

// Function prototypes
Node* createPoly(int n);
Node* insertEnd(Node* head, int c, int e);
void displayPoly(Node* head);
Node* addPoly(Node* p1, Node* p2);
void freeList(Node* head);

// Create a polynomial with n terms
Node* createPoly(int n) {
    Node *head = NULL, *temp = NULL;
    int c, e;
    printf("Enter terms in DESCENDING order of exponent:\n");
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        printf("  Term %d - coefficient and exponent: ", i + 1);
        scanf("%d %d", &c, &e);
        Node *newNode = (Node*)malloc(sizeof(Node));
        newNode->coeff = c;
        newNode->expo = e;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;
            temp = newNode;
        } else {
            temp->next = newNode;
            temp = newNode;
        }
    }
    return head;
}

// Display polynomial in readable form
void displayPoly(Node* head) {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("0");
        return;
    }
    Node* t = head;
    while (t != NULL) {
        if (t->coeff > 0 && t != head) printf(" + ");
        if (t->coeff < 0) printf(" - ");
        if (t->expo == 0) printf("%d", abs(t->coeff));
        else if (t->expo == 1) printf("%dx", abs(t->coeff));
        else printf("%dx^%d", abs(t->coeff), t->expo);
        t = t->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}

// Add two polynomials and return new list
Node* addPoly(Node* p1, Node* p2) {
    Node *result = NULL, *tail = NULL;
    while (p1 != NULL && p2 != NULL) {
        int c, e;
        if (p1->expo == p2->expo) {
            c = p1->coeff + p2->coeff;
            e = p1->expo;
            p1 = p1->next;
            p2 = p2->next;
            if (c == 0) continue;   // skip zero terms
        } else if (p1->expo > p2->expo) {
            c = p1->coeff;
            e = p1->expo;
            p1 = p1->next;
        } else {
            c = p2->coeff;
            e = p2->expo;
            p2 = p2->next;
        }
        Node* newNode = (Node*)malloc(sizeof(Node));
        newNode->coeff = c;
        newNode->expo = e;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        if (result == NULL) {
            result = newNode;
            tail = newNode;
        } else {
            tail->next = newNode;
            tail = newNode;
        }
    }
    while (p1 != NULL) {
        Node* newNode = (Node*)malloc(sizeof(Node));
        newNode->coeff = p1->coeff;
        newNode->expo = p1->expo;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        tail->next = newNode;
        tail = newNode;
        p1 = p1->next;
    }
    while (p2 != NULL) {
        Node* newNode = (Node*)malloc(sizeof(Node));
        newNode->coeff = p2->coeff;
        newNode->expo = p2->expo;
        newNode->next = NULL;
        tail->next = newNode;
        tail = newNode;
        p2 = p2->next;
    }
    return result;
}

// Free all allocated memory
void freeList(Node* head) {
    Node* t;
    while (head != NULL) {
        t = head;
        head = head->next;
        free(t);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n1, n2;
    printf("Number of terms in Polynomial 1: ");
    scanf("%d", &n1);
    Node* P1 = createPoly(n1);
    printf("Number of terms in Polynomial 2: ");
    scanf("%d", &n2);
    Node* P2 = createPoly(n2);
    printf("\nP1(x) = "); displayPoly(P1);
    printf("P2(x) = "); displayPoly(P2);
    Node* sum = addPoly(P1, P2);
    printf("Sum  = "); displayPoly(sum);
    freeList(P1);
    freeList(P2);
    freeList(sum);
    return 0;
}
```

## 3.4 Analytical Matrix: Sample Input/Output

```
Input:
  Number of terms in Polynomial 1: 3
  Term 1: 4 5
  Term 2: 3 2
  Term 3: 7 0
  Number of terms in Polynomial 2: 3
  Term 1: 6 5
