## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Academic Definition (KTU 2024 Syllabus Terminology)

A **Doubly Linked List (DLL)** is a linear, dynamic, sequential data structure belonging to the family of linked lists, in which every node maintains **two distinct pointer fields** — one pointing to its **immediate predecessor** (`prev`) and another pointing to its **immediate successor** (`next`) — in addition to the data field. The collection of such nodes, chained together via bidirectional pointers and anchored by a `head` pointer (and optionally a `tail` pointer), constitutes a Doubly Linked List.

According to the **KTU 2024 Scheme** definition for *PCEOL308 – Data Structures Lab*, a DLL is contrasted against the Singly Linked List (SLL) by emphasizing the **bidirectional traversal capability** and the **O(1) deletion of a node given only its reference**, both of which are the central learning outcomes of Experiment 2.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Syllabus Highlight (KTU 2024 Scheme – Module 2):** Students must implement, debug, and analyze operations including *creation, insertion (front/end/position), deletion (front/end/position/key), forward traversal, backward traversal, and search* on a Doubly Linked List using the **C programming language** in a Linux/GCC environment.

### 1.2 The Node Anatomy (Conceptual Foundation)

Each node in a DLL is composed of **three logically distinct parts**:

| Field | Purpose | Memory Footprint (Typical `int` system) |
| :- | :- | :- |
| `data` | Stores the payload value (any user-defined type) | **4 bytes** (for `int`) |
| `prev` | Pointer to the previous node (or `NULL` for the first node) | **8 bytes** (on 64-bit) |
| `next` | Pointer to the next node (or `NULL` for the last node) | **8 bytes** (on 64-bit) |

The total size per node on a typical 64-bit GCC compiler is therefore **20 bytes** (with padding it rounds to **24 bytes**).

### 1.3 Conceptual Analogy — Plain English Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Analogy: The Music Playlist on a Stereo with a "Previous" Button**
> Imagine your favourite music player where every song on the playlist is connected to *both* the song that came before it **and** the song that comes after it. If you are currently listening to song number 5, you can press the **Next** button to jump to song 6, or the **Previous** button to go back to song 4 — all in a single click. You do not have to scroll back to the top of the playlist to find song 4.
>
> A **Doubly Linked List** is exactly this playlist. Every song (node) knows about the song before it (`prev` pointer) and the song after it (`next` pointer). The **first song's** `prev` pointer is `NULL` (no song before it), and the **last song's** `next` pointer is `NULL` (no song after it). The `head` pointer is like the play button — it always tells you where to start.

### 1.4 Formal Node Structure in C

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *prev;
    struct Node *next;
};

typedef struct Node Node;
```

> [!NOTE]
> **Naming Convention Used in KTU Labs:** The convention is `struct Node` with lowercase pointer names (`head`, `tail`, `newNode`, `temp`) — this is the **expected style in KTU board viva evaluations** as per 2024 Scheme lab rubrics.
