## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet

### 2.1 The Core "Why" Behind Each DLL Operation

Unlike an array where every element has a fixed index-based position, a DLL uses **pointer chaining**. Therefore, every operation on a DLL is fundamentally a **pointer-rewiring exercise**. Understanding the "Why" behind the pointer changes is the single most important skill for the KTU lab viva.

- **Why does a DLL need two pointers per node?**
  The bidirectional pointer enables **reverse traversal** without recursion and allows a node to know its predecessor, which is essential for **O(1) deletion** when given a node's address (contrast with SLL which must walk from head).

- **Why is DLL preferred over SLL for certain operations?**
  Given a node pointer `n`, deletion in SLL requires traversal from `head` to find `n->prev` (costly). In DLL, `n->prev` is immediately available → **O(1) deletion given a reference**.

- **Why is DLL memory-heavy?**
  Each node stores **two pointers** instead of one, increasing memory overhead by approximately **8 bytes per node** on a 64-bit system.

### 2.2 The Seven Canonical DLL Operations

The KTU 2024 Scheme Experiment 2 expects mastery of the following operations:

1. **Create Node** – Allocate memory using `malloc()`, initialize `prev = NULL`, `next = NULL`.
2. **Insert at Beginning** – O(1) — Update only `head->prev` and `head`.
3. **Insert at End** – O(n) without tail pointer, O(1) with tail pointer.
4. **Insert at Position** – O(n) — Traverse to `(pos - 1)`, rewire four pointers.
5. **Delete from Beginning** – O(1) — Free old head, advance `head`.
6. **Delete from End** – O(n) — Traverse to last node, free, set second-last's `next = NULL`.
7. **Delete by Value/Key** – O(n) — Search + pointer rewire + `free()`.

### 2.3 KTU High-Yield Cheat Sheet — Time Complexity Table

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Memorize this table — it is a guaranteed 3-mark question in Part A or a sub-part in Part B.**

| Operation | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Reason |
| :- | :- | :- | :- |
| Insertion at Beginning | **O(1)** | O(1) | Only `head` and `newNode->next` are touched |
| Insertion at End (no tail) | **O(n)** | O(1) | Must traverse whole list to find last node |
| Insertion at End (with tail) | **O(1)** | O(1) | `tail->next = newNode` directly |
| Insertion at Position `p` | **O(n)** | O(1) | Worst case traverse `p - 1` nodes |
| Deletion at Beginning | **O(1)** | O(1) | Just `head = head->next; head->prev = NULL` |
| Deletion at End | **O(n)** | O(1) | Must reach the second-last node |
| Deletion at Position `p` | **O(n)** | O(1) | Traversal + 4-pointer rewire |
| Search by Value | **O(n)** | O(1) | Linear scan, no random access |
| Forward Traversal | **O(n)** | O(1) | Follow `next` pointers |
| Backward Traversal | **O(n)** | O(1) | Follow `prev` pointers |
| Reverse the List | **O(n)** | O(1) | Swap `prev` and `next` for every node |

