**Q A(b). Write a C function to insert a new node at a given position `pos` in a non-empty Doubly Linked List. Handle edge cases for invalid positions and insertion at position 1.**
**[7 Marks]**

**Model Solution:**

```c
void insertAtPos(Node **head, int x, int pos) {
    if (pos < 1) { printf("Invalid position\n"); return; }
    if (pos == 1) { insertBeginning(head, x); return; }

    Node *temp = *head;
    for (int i = 1; i < pos - 1 && temp != NULL; i++)
        temp = temp->next;

    if (temp == NULL) { printf("Position out of range\n"); return; }

    Node *n = createNode(x);
    n->next = temp->next;
    if (temp->next != NULL) temp->next->prev = n;
    temp->next = n;
    n->prev = temp;
    printf("%d inserted at position %d\n", x, pos);
}
```

**Step-by-step Trace for `insertAtPos(head, 25, 3)` when list is `10 <-> 20 <-> 30`:**

$$
\begin{aligned}
\text{Iteration 1:} \quad & i = 1, \quad \text{temp at 10}, \quad \text{not equal to } pos-1 = 2 \\
\text{Iteration 2:} \quad & i = 2, \quad \text{temp at 20}, \quad \text{loop exits} \\
\text{Rewire:} \quad & \text{n->next = temp->next (i.e., 30)} \\
& \text{30->prev = n} \\
& \text{temp->next (20->next) = n} \\
& \text{n->prev = temp (20)} \\
\text{Final List:} \quad & 10 \leftrightarrow 20 \leftrightarrow 25 \leftrightarrow 30 \rightarrow \text{NULL}
\end{aligned}
$$

