**Q B(b). Explain with a neat diagram and a C function how to traverse a Doubly Linked List in both forward and backward directions. Justify why DLL supports O(1) reverse traversal given a `tail` pointer, while SLL does not.**
**[7 Marks]**

**Model Solution:**

**Forward Traversal Function:**

```c
void traverseForward(Node *head) {
    printf("Forward: ");
    while (head != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", head->data);
        head = head->next;
    }
    printf("\n");
}
```

**Backward Traversal Function (without tail — full traversal needed):**

```c
void traverseBackward(Node *head) {
    if (head == NULL) { printf("Backward: NULL\n"); return; }
    while (head->next != NULL) head = head->next; /* Go to last node */
    printf("Backward: ");
    while (head != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", head->data);
        head = head->prev;
    }
    printf("\n");
}
```

**Backward Traversal with `tail` pointer (O(1) start):**

```c
void traverseBackwardFromTail(Node *tail) {
    printf("Backward: ");
    while (tail != NULL) {
        printf("%d ", tail->data);
        tail = tail->prev;
    }
    printf("\n");
}
```

**Diagram — Bidirectional Pointer Flow:**

```mermaid
flowchart LR
    H[head] --> A["Node: 10"] --> B["Node: 20"] --> C["Node: 30"] --> N["NULL"]
    N -. prev .-> A
    A -. prev .-> H
    B -. prev .-> A
    C -. prev .-> B
    T[tail] -.-> C

    classDef head fill:#FFD700,stroke:#000,color:#000
    classDef node fill:#87CEEB,stroke:#000,color:#000
    classDef null fill:#FF6B6B,stroke:#000,color:#000
    classDef tail fill:#90EE90,stroke:#000,color:#000
    class H head
    class A,B,C node
    class N null
    class T tail
```

**Justification — DLL vs SLL for Reverse Traversal:**

- **DLL with `tail` pointer:** Reverse traversal starts at `tail` and follows `prev` pointers. Each step is **O(1)**, so traversing `n` nodes takes **O(n)** with no extra setup.
- **DLL without `tail` pointer:** We first traverse forward to reach the last node (O(n)), then use `prev` pointers to go backward (O(n)). Total = **O(n)**.
- **SLL:** Cannot traverse backward at all directly because each node only has a `next` pointer. To reverse, we either (a) reverse the list in-place (O(n)) or (b) use recursion with O(n) stack space. There is **no direct backward navigation** because `prev` information is lost.

Therefore, **DLL is structurally superior for reverse traversal** because every node stores its predecessor pointer explicitly, whereas SLL nodes discard that information.

