### 5.5 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

> [!NOTE]
> **Rapid-Revision Checklist for KTU Board Viva & ESE:**

- A **Doubly Linked List** node has **three fields**: `data`, `prev`, `next`. Total ~**24 bytes** on 64-bit GCC.
- The **first node's** `prev` is `NULL`; the **last node's** `next` is `NULL`.
- **Insertion at beginning is O(1)** because no traversal is needed; only `head` and the new node's `next` are touched.
- **Insertion at end without `tail` is O(n)** because we must walk the entire list to find the last node.
- **Deletion at beginning is O(1)** because we just advance `head` and set `head->prev = NULL`.
- **Deletion at end is O(n)** because we need to reach the second-last node to set `next = NULL`.
- **DLL enables O(1) deletion given a node reference** — this is the key advantage over SLL.
- Always pass `Node **head` (double pointer) when modifying `head` itself.
- Always initialize `prev = NULL` and `next = NULL` in `createNode` to prevent garbage values.
- Always check `head == NULL` **before** accessing `head->next` or `head->prev` to avoid segmentation faults.
- After every deletion, call `free()` to prevent **memory leaks** — Valgrind-clean code is a KTU viva scoring criterion.
- Forward traversal uses `temp = temp->next`; backward traversal uses `temp = temp->prev`.
- The **menu-driven main** must offer: Create, Insert (Begin/End/Pos), Delete (Begin/End/Key), Display (Forward/Backward), Search, Exit.
- **Time complexity formula** (general): For any position-based operation on a DLL with `n` nodes, worst-case complexity is **O(n)** and best-case is **O(1)** (at boundaries).
- **Space complexity** of all DLL operations is **O(1)** auxiliary (excluding input/output space).
- The **Linux kernel** uses DLLs in its `list.h` for managing task lists, drivers, and memory pages — a strong real-world justification to mention in viva answers.
- In reverse-traversal problems, mention that SLL cannot do it without **recursion (O(n) stack) or list reversal (O(n))**, whereas DLL does it natively using `prev` pointers.
- The classic **LRU Cache** uses a DLL + HashMap to achieve **O(1) get/put** — this is a frequent viva "bonus" question worth mentioning if asked about real-world applications.
