## 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

### 2.1 Operational Logic Breakdown

A circular linked list differs from a singly linear linked list in two critical ways:

- **No `NULL` terminator** at the end → traversal loop termination requires checking `temp->next == head`.
- **Head node is the only persistent reference**; traversing the full list is **O(n)**, not O(n) with a clean exit.

#### Bulleted Logic for Core Operations

**Step 1 — Creation of CLL**
- Read the number of nodes `n`.
- For each node: `malloc()` → `head = temp` if first, else `prev->next = temp`.
- After all nodes: `last->next = head`.

**Step 2 — Insertion Operations**
- *Insert at Front:* New node's `next = head`; traverse to last node; `last->next = newNode`; `head = newNode`.
- *Insert at End:* Traverse to last; `newNode->next = head`; `last->next = newNode`.
- *Insert at Position k:* Traverse to `(k-1)`-th node; `newNode->next = temp->next`; `temp->next = newNode`.

**Step 3 — Deletion Operations**
- *Delete Front:* `temp = head`; traverse to last; `last->next = head->next`; `head = head->next`; `free(temp)`.
- *Delete End:* Traverse to second-last; `free(last->next)`; `secondLast->next = head`.
- *Delete Position k:* Traverse to `(k-1)`; `temp = curr->next`; `curr->next = temp->next`; `free(temp)`.

**Step 4 — Traversal / Display**
- Start at `head`, print `data`, move to `next`.
- **Termination condition:** `do-while` loop terminating when `temp == head` after first print.

**Step 5 — Search Operation**
- Traverse using `do-while`; compare each `node->data` with key.
- Return `1` (found) or `0` (not found).

### 2.2 KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

| Operation | Time Complexity | Space Complexity | Termination Condition |
|---|---|---|---|
| Create CLL | **O(n)** | **O(n)** | All `n` nodes allocated |
| Insert at Front | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `last->next = newHead` |
| Insert at End | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `newNode->next = head` |
| Insert at Position k | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `prev->next = newNode` |
| Delete at Front | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `head = head->next` |
| Delete at End | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `secondLast->next = head` |
| Traverse/Display | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `temp->next == head` |
| Search Element | **O(n)** | **O(1)** | `temp->data == key` |

> [!NOTE]
> **Critical Invariant Formula:**
> $$\text{If } \text{head} \neq \text{NULL} \implies \text{last} \rightarrow \text{next} = \text{head}$$
> Violation of this invariant means the list is no longer "circular".

### 2.3 Real-World Engineering Utility

- **Operating Systems:** Round-Robin CPU scheduling uses a **circular linked list** to maintain process queues, where the scheduler wraps around to the head after exhausting the list.
- **Buffer Management:** Circular buffers in audio/video streaming applications (ring buffers) are implemented using circular linked lists.
- **Gaming Applications:** Multiplayer turn-based games (e.g., Ludo) cycle through players using a CLL.
- **Network Token Ring Topology:** A token circulates among nodes in a closed loop — classic CLL analogy.

