## 5. KTU 2024 Scheme Examination Question Bank & Topic Recap

### 5.1 Part A Questions (3 Marks Each)

---

**Q1. [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**
*Define a Circular Linked List. How is it different from a Singly Linked List?*

**Model Answer:**
A **Circular Linked List (CLL)** is a linked list in which the last node's `next` pointer does not point to `NULL` but instead points back to the **head (first) node**, forming a closed loop. This circular linkage enables traversal from any node to reach any other node without a terminating NULL marker.

**Key Differences:**

| Feature | Singly Linked List | Circular Linked List |
|---|---|---|
| Last node `next` | `NULL` | `head` (first node) |
| Traversal termination | `temp == NULL` | `temp == head` (do-while) |
| Memory overhead | Lower (uses NULL as sentinel) | Same node size |
| Applications | Linear storage | Round-robin scheduling, ring buffers |

**(3 Marks)**

---

**Q2. [KTU University Exam – May 2024]**
*Write the node structure for a Circular Linked List in C. Why must we use a `do-while` loop for traversal?*

**Model Answer:**

```c
struct Node {
    int data;
    struct Node *next;
};
```

**Reason for `do-while`:** In a Circular Linked List, the **head itself is the only reference point** and the list has no `NULL` terminator. A `while` loop would never execute its body if we used the condition `temp != NULL` (since the head is non-NULL, the loop would never terminate properly). Hence, a `do-while` loop is mandatory so that the body executes at least once and terminates when `temp == head` again — a circular path is naturally traversed.

**(3 Marks)**

---

### 5.2 Part B Questions (14 Marks Each)

---

### **Question A (14 Marks)**

**[KTU University Exam – May 2024, Model Paper 2]**

**(a)** Write a C program to create a Circular Linked List of `n` nodes by inserting each new node at the **rear (end)** of the list. Display the final list. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a C function to insert a new node at the **front** of an existing Circular Linked List. Explain how the head pointer is updated. **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution:

**(a) Creation of CLL by rear insertion:**

```c
struct Node* createCLL(int n) {
    struct Node *head = NULL, *temp = NULL, *newNode = NULL;
    int value, i;
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        scanf("%d", &value);
        newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
        newNode->data = value;
        if (head == NULL) {
            head = newNode;
            newNode->next = head;
        } else {
            temp = head;
            while (temp->next != head)
                temp = temp->next;
            temp->next = newNode;
            newNode->next = head;
        }
    }
    return head;
}
```

**Explanation:** For each new node, we traverse to the last node (where `temp->next == head`), attach the new node, and re-establish the circular link by setting `newNode->next = head`. Time complexity is **O(n²)** for naive creation, but **O(n)** with a tail pointer optimization.

**(b) Insert at Front:**

```c
struct Node* insertFront(struct Node *head, int value) {
    struct Node *newNode = (struct Node*)malloc(sizeof(struct Node));
    newNode->data = value;
    newNode->next = head;

    if (head == NULL) {
        newNode->next = newNode;
        return newNode;
    }
    struct Node *temp = head;
    while (temp->next != head)
        temp = temp->next;       // Traverse to last node
    temp->next = newNode;        // Re-link last to new head
    head = newNode;              // Update HEAD pointer
    return head;
}
```

**Head Pointer Update Logic:** After insertion, the **memory address of the new node** becomes the new `head`. The function returns this new `head` so that the caller's `head` variable in `main()` is updated — this is critical because C uses **pass-by-value** for pointers. **(7 Marks)**

---

### **Question B (14 Marks) — Alternative Choice**

**[KTU University Exam – Dec 2023]**

**(a)** Write a C function to **delete the last node** of a Circular Linked List. Handle the edge case of a single-node list. **(7 Marks)**

**(b)** Write a C function to **search for a given key** in a Circular Linked List. What is the time complexity? **(7 Marks)**

#### Model Solution:

**(a) Delete Last Node:**

```c
struct Node* deleteEnd(struct Node *head) {
    if (head == NULL) {
        printf("List is EMPTY.\n");
        return NULL;
    }
    // Edge Case: Single node
    if (head->next == head) {
        free(head);
        return NULL;
    }
    // General Case: Traverse to second-last node
    struct Node *temp = head;
    while (temp->next->next != head)
        temp = temp->next;

    free(temp->next);            // Free the last node
    temp->next = head;           // Re-link second-last to head
    return head;
}
```

**Edge Case Handling:** If `head->next == head`, the list contains only one node (self-loop). Free it and return `NULL` to indicate an empty list. **(7 Marks)**

**(b) Search Operation:**

```c
int search(struct Node *head, int key) {
    if (head == NULL) return 0;
    struct Node *temp = head;
    do {
        if (temp->data == key) return 1;   // Found
        temp = temp->next;
    } while (temp != head);
    return 0;                              // Not found
}
```

**Time Complexity Analysis:**

$$
T(n) = \begin{cases}
O(1) & \text{if key is at head (best case)} \\
O(n) & \text{if key is at the last node or absent (worst case)} \\
O\left(\frac{n}{2}\right) & \text{average case (linear search)}
\end{cases}
$$

A `do-while` loop ensures **at least one iteration** even if the list contains a single node, and it terminates cleanly when we circle back to the head. **(7 Marks)**

---

> [!WARNING]
> **KTU Examiner's Valuation Warning / Common Pitfalls:**
> 1. **Forgetting to update the `head` pointer** after `insertFront()` or `deleteFront()` — students lose **2 marks** for this since C is pass-by-value.
> 2. **Using `while` instead of `do-while`** for traversal — the loop will fail to terminate or skip the head node entirely, costing **1–2 marks**.
> 3. **Forgetting the `last->next = head` re-linking** after deletion — this breaks the circular invariant, **2 marks deducted**.
> 4. **Not freeing memory** after deletion — examiner deducts **1 mark** for memory leak.
> 5. **Wrong edge case for single-node list** — if `head->next == head`, naive code crashes. Examiner watches for this closely.

---

### 5.3 Topic Recap & Important Things to Remember

- A **Circular Linked List** is a linked list where the last node points back to the head, forming a loop.
- The **defining invariant** is: `last->next == head` (always true when list is non-empty).
- Use a **`do-while` loop** for traversal with the termination condition `temp == head`.
- **Insertion at front** requires traversal to the last node to update its `next` → **O(n)**, but the new head must be returned.
- **Insertion at end** is also **O(n)** without a tail pointer; using a tail pointer makes it **O(1)**.
- **Deletion** operations must preserve the circular link by re-routing the second-last node to head.
- **Single-node edge case:** when `head->next == head`, the node forms a self-loop and must be freed carefully.
- **Search** is **O(n)** in worst/average case; **O(1)** best case.
- Always use **`malloc()`** for dynamic allocation and **`free()`** after deletion to prevent memory leaks.
- The **HEAD pointer** is the only entry point; updates to it must propagate via return value (no pass-by-reference in C).
- **Applications:** Round-Robin scheduling, circular buffers (ring buffers), token ring networks, multiplayer game turns.
- **Difference from Doubly CLL:** Doubly CLL has both `next` and `prev` pointers, allowing reverse traversal.

