# MODULE EXPERIMENT 2: IMPLEMENTATION OF BFS AND DFS ON GRAPH

## 1. Core Technical Definition & Intuitive Overview

### 1.1 Formal Definition of Graph Traversal

A **Graph Traversal** (also called Graph Search) is the systematic process of visiting (checking and/or updating) every vertex in a graph exactly once in a defined order. For a graph $G = (V, E)$ where $V$ represents the set of vertices and $E$ the set of edges, a traversal algorithm produces a linear ordering of vertices that respects the connectivity structure of $G$.

**Breadth-First Search (BFS)** is a vertex-based graph traversal algorithm that explores all vertices at the present depth level before moving on to the vertices at the next depth level. It uses a **FIFO (First-In-First-Out) Queue** data structure to keep track of the frontier of unexplored vertices.

**Depth-First Search (DFS)** is a vertex-based graph traversal algorithm that explores as far as possible down each branch before backtracking. It uses a **LIFO (Last-In-First-Out) Stack** data structure (or system recursion stack) to remember the vertices to visit next.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **KTU 2024 Syllabus Highlight:** Both BFS and DFS are classified as **O(V + E)** time complexity algorithms where V is the number of vertices and E is the number of edges in the graph. They form the foundation for solving advanced problems like shortest path (unweighted), cycle detection, topological sorting, and connected component analysis.

### 1.2 Conceptual Analogy / Intuition

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy 1 — BFS (Ripples in a Pond):**
> Imagine dropping a stone into the center of a still pond. The ripples spread outward in concentric circles. The first circle reaches stones at distance 1, then distance 2, then distance 3, and so on. BFS works exactly like this: it visits all "neighbors" (distance 1) first, then all "neighbors of neighbors" (distance 2), expanding outward layer by layer. The **queue** acts like a waiting list — "I'll process you in the exact order you were discovered."

> [!NOTE]
> **Real-World Analogy 2 — DFS (Exploring a Maze):**
> Imagine you are trapped in a maze with a piece of chalk and a ball of string. You walk down a path, marking each turn. When you hit a dead-end, you retrace your steps (backtrack) to the last junction where you made a choice, and try a new path. DFS follows this "go as deep as possible, then backtrack" strategy. The **stack** (or recursion) acts like the chalk marks — remembering "where I came from" so I can return when stuck.

### 1.3 Graph Representation Methods

For implementing BFS/DFS in C programming (as expected in KTU lab exams), graphs are typically represented in two ways:

| Representation | Storage Formula | Best Use Case |
|---|---|---|
| **Adjacency Matrix** | 2D array of size $V \times V$ | Dense graphs, O(1) edge lookup |
| **Adjacency List** | Array of Linked Lists / Array of Vectors | Sparse graphs, space efficient |

**Memory Footprint Comparison:**
- Adjacency Matrix: $\Theta(V^2)$ space
- Adjacency List: $\Theta(V + E)$ space
