# 2. Deep Theoretical Analysis & KTU High-Yield Formula Sheet

## 2.1 BFS — Operational Logic Decomposition

The BFS algorithm follows these structured steps:

1. **Initialize:** Create a `visited[]` array of size $V$ and set all entries to `0` (FALSE). Create an empty queue `Q`.
2. **Source Selection:** Choose a start vertex $s$. Mark `visited[s] = 1` and `Enqueue(Q, s)`.
3. **Main Loop:** While `Q` is **NOT empty**, repeat:
   - **Step 3a:** `v = Dequeue(Q)` — remove the oldest vertex.
   - **Step 3b:** Process/Print `v` (this is the "visit" moment).
   - **Step 3c:** For every vertex `u` adjacent to `v`:
     - If `visited[u] == 0`, then set `visited[u] = 1` and `Enqueue(Q, u)`.
4. **Termination:** The queue becomes empty exactly when all reachable vertices from `s` have been visited.

### 2.2 DFS — Operational Logic Decomposition

The DFS algorithm follows these structured steps:

1. **Initialize:** Create a `visited[]` array of size $V$ and set all entries to `0` (FALSE). Create an empty stack `S`.
2. **Source Selection:** Choose a start vertex $s`. Mark `visited[s] = 1` and `Push(S, s)`.
3. **Main Loop:** While `S` is **NOT empty**, repeat:
   - **Step 3a:** `v = Pop(S)` — remove the most recent vertex.
   - **Step 3b:** Process/Print `v` (this is the "visit" moment).
   - **Step 3c:** For every vertex `u` adjacent to `v`:
     - If `visited[u] == 0`, then set `visited[u] = 1` and `Push(S, u)`.
4. **Recursion Alternative:** DFS can also be implemented as a recursive function `DFS(v)` that marks and prints `v`, then recursively calls `DFS(u)` for each unvisited neighbor `u`.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **The "Why" Behind the Logic:**
> - In BFS, the **queue's FIFO nature** guarantees that vertices discovered earlier are processed earlier → this produces the **level-order (shortest-path) property**.
> - In DFS, the **stack's LIFO nature** (or recursion) guarantees that we always dive deeper before exploring siblings → this produces the **backtracking property**.

## 2.3 KTU Formula Sheet / Cheat Sheet

| Parameter | BFS Formula | DFS Formula | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Time Complexity (Adjacency Matrix)** | $O(V^2)$ | $O(V^2)$ | Each vertex scans all V entries |
| **Time Complexity (Adjacency List)** | $O(V + E)$ | $O(V + E)$ | Each edge examined once |
| **Space Complexity** | $O(V)$ | $O(V)$ | For visited[] and queue/stack |
| **Data Structure Used** | Queue (FIFO) | Stack (LIFO) / Recursion | Core distinction |
| **Traversal Order** | Level-by-level (Breadth) | Branch-by-branch (Depth) | Behavioural distinction |
| **Shortest Path (unweighted)** | ✅ Yes (guaranteed) | ❌ No (not guaranteed) | KTU favourite question |
| **Cycle Detection (undirected)** | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes | BFS uses parent tracking |
| **Memory per Vertex** | $O(1)$ extra | $O(V)$ worst case (deep recursion) | Stack depth issue |

### 2.4 Boundary Conditions and Edge Cases

> [!WARNING]
> **Critical Edge Cases Every KTU Student Must Handle:**
> 1. **Disconnected Graph:** A single BFS/DFS call from one source will NOT visit all vertices. You must wrap the main function in a `for v = 0 to V-1` loop to handle every component.
> 2. **Self-Loop:** An edge from a vertex to itself. Adjacency list must avoid duplicate insertions.
> 3. **No Edges (Isolated Vertices):** Vertex is still valid — must be visited even if it has no neighbors.
> 4. **Stack Overflow in DFS:** For deep graphs (e.g., a path graph with 100,000 nodes), recursive DFS may crash due to stack overflow. Use iterative DFS in production code.

### 2.5 Real-World Engineering Utility

| Domain | BFS Application | DFS Application |
|---|---|---|
| **Social Networks (Facebook)** | Finding people within "N degrees of connection" | Suggesting friends (exploring friend-of-friend chains) |
| **GPS Navigation (Google Maps)** | Finding shortest route (unweighted) | Exploring all possible routes in routing problems |
| **AI / Game Playing** | — | Solving mazes, puzzles (Sudoku, N-Queens) |
| **Web Crawlers** | Crawling pages in breadth order | Deep indexing of linked pages |
| **Compiler Design** | — | Topological sort, cycle detection in dependency graphs |
| **Network Broadcasting** | Packets spread in waves | Single-path message routing |
| **Garbage Collection** | Mark-and-sweep collectors | — |

> [!NOTE]
> **KTU Examiner Insight:** When asked "Where is BFS used in real life?", the highest-scoring answer explicitly mentions **"shortest path in unweighted graphs"** or **"level-order tree traversal"**. For DFS, mention **"cycle detection"** or **"topological sorting"**.
