# 3. Step-by-Step Derivations & Analytical Matrix

## 3.1 Complete C Program: BFS on Adjacency Matrix (KTU Lab Standard)

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 20

int adj[MAX][MAX];
int visited[MAX];
int n;  // number of vertices

void BFS(int start) {
    int queue[MAX], front = 0, rear = 0;
    int v, i;

    // Step 1: Mark start as visited and enqueue
    visited[start] = 1;
    queue[rear++] = start;
    printf("BFS Traversal: ");

    // Step 2: Process queue until empty
    while (front < rear) {
        v = queue[front++];      // Dequeue
        printf("%d ", v);        // Visit

        // Step 3: Enqueue all unvisited neighbors
        for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (adj[v][i] == 1 && visited[i] == 0) {
                visited[i] = 1;
                queue[rear++] = i;
            }
        }
    }
    printf("\n");
}

int main() {
    int i, j, start;

    printf("Enter number of vertices: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    printf("Enter adjacency matrix (%d x %d):\n", n, n);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
            scanf("%d", &adj[i][j]);

    printf("Enter start vertex (0 to %d): ", n - 1);
    scanf("%d", &start);

    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) visited[i] = 0;
    BFS(start);
    return 0;
}
```

## 3.2 Complete C Program: DFS (Recursive) on Adjacency Matrix

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 20

int adj[MAX][MAX];
int visited[MAX];
int n;

void DFS(int v) {
    int i;

    // Step 1: Mark and visit current vertex
    visited[v] = 1;
    printf("%d ", v);

    // Step 2: Recursively visit all unvisited neighbors
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (adj[v][i] == 1 && visited[i] == 0) {
            DFS(i);  // Recursive call = implicit stack push
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int i, j, start;

    printf("Enter number of vertices: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    printf("Enter adjacency matrix (%d x %d):\n", n, n);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++)
            scanf("%d", &adj[i][j]);

    printf("Enter start vertex (0 to %d): ", n - 1);
    scanf("%d", &start);

    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) visited[i] = 0;
    printf("DFS Traversal: ");
    DFS(start);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

## 3.3 Worked Example: BFS Trace Table

**Sample Graph (5 vertices, directed):**
$$A \rightarrow B, \quad A \rightarrow C, \quad B \rightarrow D, \quad C \rightarrow D, \quad D \rightarrow E$$

Adjacency Matrix:

| | A(0) | B(1) | C(2) | D(3) | E(4) |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **A(0)** | 0 | 1 | 1 | 0 | 0 |
| **B(1)** | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1 | 0 |
| **C(2)** | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1 | 0 |
| **D(3)** | 0 | 0 | 0 | 0 | 1 |
| **E(4)** | 0 | 0 | 0 | 0 | 0 |

**BFS Trace (Start = A = vertex 0):**

| Iteration | Dequeue (v) | Output | Queue State (Front→Rear) | Visited After |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Initial | — | — | [0] | {0} |
| 1 | 0 (A) | A | [1, 2] | {0, 1, 2} |
| 2 | 1 (B) | A B | [2, 3] | {0, 1, 2, 3} |
| 3 | 2 (C) | A B C | [3] | {0, 1, 2, 3} |
| 4 | 3 (D) | A B C D | [4] | {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} |
| 5 | 4 (E) | A B C D E | [ ] | {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} |

**Final BFS Output:** `A B C D E`

> [!NOTE]
> **Observation from trace:** Notice that vertices B and C (both at distance 1 from A) are output together before D (distance 2). This is the **level-order property** of BFS.

## 3.4 Worked Example: DFS Trace Table

**Same Graph as above, DFS from A:**

| Call | v | Output | Recursive Stack (top→bottom) | Visited |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | DFS(A) | A | [A] | {A} |
| 2 | DFS(B) | A B | [B, A] | {A, B} |
| 3 | DFS(D) | A B D | [D, B, A] | {A, B, D} |
| 4 | DFS(E) | A B D E | [E, D, B, A] | {A, B, D, E} |
| 5 | return from DFS(E) | — | [D, B, A] | {A, B, D, E} |
| 6 | return to DFS(A), call DFS(C) | A B D E C | [C, A] | {A, B, C, D, E} |
| 7 | D already visited → backtrack | — | [A] | — |
| 8 | return from DFS(A) | — | [ ] | DONE |

**Final DFS Output:** `A B D E C`

> [!NOTE]
> **Observation from trace:** DFS went "deep" along the path A→B→D→E before backtracking to explore C. This is the **depth-first** behavior — the algorithm commits to a path and only explores alternatives upon dead-ends.

## 3.5 Comparison Matrix: BFS vs DFS for Same Graph

| Aspect | BFS Output | DFS Output |
|---|---|---|
| Order (from A) | A B C D E | A B D E C |
| Data Structure | Queue | Stack / Recursion |
| Memory Pattern | Stores all neighbors at level | Stores only current path |
| Shortest Path? | ✅ Yes (A to D = 2 edges) | ❌ No guarantee (A-B-D found, but order differs) |
| Level Property | Respects levels | Ignores levels |
