## 5.1 Part A — Short Answer Questions (3 Marks Each)

### **Question 1: [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023, May 2024]**
**Define Breadth-First Search (BFS). Mention the data structure used and state its time complexity.**

**Model Answer (3 marks):**

> [!NOTE]
> **Definition (1.5 marks):** Breadth-First Search (BFS) is a graph traversal algorithm that systematically visits all vertices of a graph in level-by-level order, i.e., it explores all vertices at the present depth before moving to vertices at the next depth. It begins from a given source vertex and expands outward like ripples in a pond.
>
> **Data Structure (1 mark):** BFS uses a **FIFO Queue** (First-In-First-Out) to keep track of vertices to be explored next. The queue ensures that vertices discovered earlier are processed earlier.
>
> **Time Complexity (0.5 mark):** $O(V + E)$ when adjacency list is used, where $V$ = number of vertices and $E$ = number of edges.

