### **Question B: [KTU University Exam – Dec 2023 Model Paper] (Alternative Choice)**

**(a)** Explain the **DFS algorithm** with a suitable pseudocode. State the data structure used. **(7 marks)**

**(b)** Write a recursive C program to perform **DFS traversal** on a graph represented as an adjacency matrix. Demonstrate the output on the graph: 0-1, 0-3, 1-2, 3-2, 2-4. **(7 marks)**

**Model Solution:**

**Part (a) — DFS Algorithm Explanation (7 marks):**

**Pseudocode:**
```
DFS(G, start):
    visited[start] = TRUE
    PRINT start
    FOR each vertex v adjacent to start:
        IF visited[v] == FALSE:
            DFS(G, v)        // RECURSIVE CALL
```

**Data Structure:** DFS uses a **STACK** (LIFO) implicitly through the system's recursion call stack. Each recursive call pushes a new frame onto the stack; when a vertex has no unvisited neighbors, the function returns (pops the frame).

**Key Properties to Mention (for full marks):**
- Goes as deep as possible before backtracking
- Time complexity: $O(V + E)$ for adjacency list
- Used in: cycle detection, topological sort, maze solving
- Memory: $O(V)$ for visited array + recursion stack

**Part (b) — Recursive DFS C Program (7 marks):**

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#define MAX 20

int adj[MAX][MAX], visited[MAX], n;

void DFS(int v) {
    int i;
    visited[v] = 1;
    printf("%d ", v);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        if (adj[v][i] == 1 && !visited[i]) {
            DFS(i);
        }
    }
}

int main() {
    int i, j, start = 0;
    printf("Enter n: "); scanf("%d", &n);
    printf("Enter matrix:\n");
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++)
        for (j = 0; j < n; j++) scanf("%d", &adj[i][j]);
    for (i = 0; i < n; i++) visited[i] = 0;
    printf("DFS: ");
    DFS(start);
    printf("\n");
    return 0;
}
```

**Adjacency Matrix for given graph (0-1, 0-3, 1-2, 3-2, 2-4):**

| | 0 | 1 | 2 | 3 | 4 |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| **0** | 0 | 1 | 0 | 1 | 0 |
| **1** | 1 | 0 | 1 | 0 | 0 |
| **2** | 0 | 1 | 0 | 1 | 1 |
| **3** | 1 | 0 | 1 | 0 | 0 |
| **4** | 0 | 0 | 1 | 0 | 0 |

**DFS Trace (Start = 0):**

| Call | v | Output | Stack (top→bottom) | Visited |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | DFS(0) | 0 | [0] | {0} |
| 2 | DFS(1) | 0 1 | [1, 0] | {0, 1} |
| 3 | DFS(2) | 0 1 2 | [2, 1, 0] | {0, 1, 2} |
| 4 | DFS(3) (via adj[2][3]=1) | 0 1 2 3 | [3, 2, 1, 0] | {0, 1, 2, 3} |
| 5 | adj[3][0]=1 visited, adj[3][2]=1 visited → backtrack | 0 1 2 3 | [2, 1, 0] | — |
| 6 | adj[2][4]=1, not visited → DFS(4) | 0 1 2 3 4 | [4, 2, 1, 0] | {0, 1, 2, 3, 4} |
| 7 | DFS(4) has no unvisited → return | — | [2, 1, 0] | — |
