> [!WARNING]
> **🚨 KTU EXAMINER'S VALUATION WARNING — PITFALL CALLOUT 🚨**
>
> **Common Mistakes That Cost Marks:**
>
> 1. **❌ Forgetting to initialize `visited[]` array to 0** (Loss: 1-2 marks). Always include `for (i = 0; i < n; i++) visited[i] = 0;` before calling BFS/DFS.
>
> 2. **❌ Marking vertex as visited at the wrong time.** In BFS, mark `visited[u] = 1` **when ENQUEUING** (not when dequeuing). If you mark it at dequeue, the same vertex may be enqueued multiple times → queue overflow + wrong output.
>
> 3. **❌ Not handling disconnected graphs.** If the graph has multiple components, a single BFS/DFS call only visits ONE component. Wrap the function call in `for (i = 0; i < n; i++) if (!visited[i]) BFS(i);` to handle this.
>
> 4. **❌ Confusing adjacency matrix indexing.** Remember: `adj[i][j] = 1` means edge from `i` to `j`. Reading the matrix incorrectly will give wrong traversal.
>
> 5. **❌ Forgetting to mention the data structure** in Part (a) theory questions. Always write "BFS uses **Queue**; DFS uses **Stack/Recursion**" — this is a 1-mark line item.
>
> 6. **❌ Not providing trace/output** in Part (b). Even if the code is correct, KTU examiners want to see a sample input/output trace. Always run the code mentally and write the expected output.
>
> 7. **❌ In DFS, the recursion order matters.** If `for (i = 0; i < n; i++)` is replaced with `for (i = n-1; i >= 0; i--)`, the output changes. Be consistent and mention this in viva.

